You Go, There you Are"

256
00:09:00,780 --> 00:09:02,430
by Jon Kabat-Zinn.

257
00:09:02,430 --> 00:09:04,320
He was one of the first, not the only,

258
00:09:04,320 --> 00:09:05,700
but one of the first people

259
00:09:05,700 --> 00:09:07,407
to really start popularizing meditation

260
00:09:07,407 --> 00:09:10,680
and mindfulness practices
in the United States.

261
00:09:10,680 --> 00:09:13,350
So this was in the late 1980s,

262
00:09:13,350 --> 00:09:16,020
and it was really only until recently

263
00:09:16,020 --> 00:09:18,600
that there were very few
studies of meditation,

264
00:09:18,600 --> 00:09:20,940
although those really
picked up in the '90s.

265
00:09:20,940 --> 00:09:24,540
Now you can find many,
many thousands of studies

266
00:09:24,540 --> 00:09:26,460
on meditation and their mechanistic basis,

267
00:09:26,460 --> 00:09:29,400
so brain imaging studies,
changes in hormones in the body.

268
00:09:29,400 --> 00:09:32,760
But in the late 1980s
and in the early 1990s,

269
00:09:32,760 --> 00:09:34,740
because functional imaging of the brain,

270
00:09:34,740 --> 00:09:38,820
so-called MRI or fMRI, was
really just starting to emerge

271
00:09:38,820 --> 00:09:41,670
as a popular tool in
laboratories and hospitals,

272
00:09:41,670 --> 00:09:43,770
there really wasn't that much
mechanistic understanding

273
00:09:43,770 --> 00:09:45,240
about how meditation worked,

274
00:09:45,240 --> 00:09:47,580
but, of course, there
was a deep understanding

275
00:09:47,580 --> 00:09:50,190
from cultures outside the United States

276
00:09:50,190 --> 00:09:52,620
that meditation was extremely useful.

277
00:09:52,620 --> 00:09:53,490
I should just mention,

278
00:09:53,490 --> 00:09:56,010
as long as we're talking about
the history of meditation,

279
00:09:56,010 --> 00:09:58,110
any discussion about meditation

280
00:09:58,110 --> 00:10:00,780
is going to be a discussion
about states of mind,

281
00:10:00,780 --> 00:10:02,790
and any discussion about states of mind

282
00:10:02,790 --> 00:10:04,260
invokes the word consciousness,

283
00:10:04,260 --> 00:10:07,920
a kind of a dangerous topic
to get into in any format

284
00:10:07,920 --> 00:10:11,010
because a lot of people
talk about consciousness,

285
00:10:11,010 --> 00:10:14,070
but people use consciousness, the word,

286
00:10:14,070 --> 00:10:15,180
to mean different things.

287
00:10:15,180 --> 00:10:17,700
It doesn't have one standard
operational definition

288
00:10:17,700 --> 00:10:19,470
as scientists call it.

289
00:10:19,470 --> 00:10:22,170
However, discussions about consciousness

290
00:10:22,170 --> 00:10:25,080
are often part and
parcel with conversations

291
00:10:25,080 --> 00:10:27,000
about things like psychedelics

292
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:28,890
and kind of alternative therapies.

293
00:10:28,890 --> 00:10:32,010
And so in the 1960s and
especially in the 1970s,

294
00:10:32,010 --> 00:10:35,910
meditation and psychedelics
were actually close cousins

295
00:10:35,910 --> 00:10:39,210
in the conversation about
consciousness and states of mind.

296
00:10:39,210 --> 00:10:41,940
That conversation started to split

297
00:10:41,940 --> 00:10:43,530
into two different divisions,

298
00:10:43,530 --> 00:10:45,600
and I'll explain why in a moment.

299
00:10:45,600 --> 00:10:48,570
It gets to a little bit of
interesting academic sociology.

300
00:10:48,570 --> 00:10:50,580
But what happened was
there were a couple of guys

301
00:10:50,580 --> 00:10:54,210
at Harvard, including
Timothy Leary and others,

302
00:10:54,210 --> 00:10:56,580
who got really interested in psychedelics,

303
00:10:56,580 --> 00:11:00,180
in particular LSD,
lysergic acid diethylamide.

304
00:11:00,180 --> 00:11:01,410
And at that time,

305
00:11:01,410 --> 00:11:03,360
that was part of the whole
counterculture movement,

306
00:11:03,360 --> 00:11:05,400
it was considered very anti-establishment,

307
00:11:05,400 --> 00:11:08,580
and they were really
encouraging students at Harvard

308
00:11:08,580 --> 00:11:10,620
to take LSD.

309
00:11:10,620 --> 00:11:12,810
They were also very
interested in meditation.

310
00:11:12,810 --> 00:11:13,890
But what ended up happening

311
00:11:13,890 --> 00:11:16,920
is they essentially got kicked
out or fired from Harvard,

312
00:11:16,920 --> 00:11:18,630
and there's a book that I'll refer you to

313
00:11:18,630 --> 00:11:19,710
in the show note captions

314
00:11:19,710 --> 00:11:21,330
if you're interested in
learning more about all this.

315
00:11:21,330 --> 00:11:22,710
But they got kicked out and fired

316
00:11:22,710 --> 00:11:24,780
for their emphasis on psychedelics.

317
00:11:24,780 --> 00:11:27,720
Now, nowadays, there's a lot
of interest in psychedelics.

318
00:11:27,720 --> 00:11:30,060
We've had episodes with
Dr. Matthew Johnson

319
00:11:30,060 --> 00:11:32,670
from Johns Hopkins University
who's running clinical trials

320
00:11:32,670 --> 00:11:34,650
on psychedelics like psilocybin and LSD

321
00:11:34,650 --> 00:11:37,050
for the treatment of depression and PTSD.

322
00:11:37,050 --> 00:11:39,720
We've also had Dr. Nolan
Williams on the podcast,

323
00:11:39,720 --> 00:11:42,480
my colleague at Stanford
who's doing incredible studies

324
00:11:42,480 --> 00:11:44,100
on some of those compounds as well.

325
00:11:44,100 --> 00:11:46,020
So nowadays, the conversation
about psychedelics

326
00:11:46,020 --> 00:11:47,070
is coming back,

327
00:11:47,070 --> 00:11:48,660
and it's somewhat divorced

328
00:11:48,660 --> 00:11:50,730
from the conversation about meditation,

329
00:11:50,730 --> 00:11:53,490
but in the 1960s and 1970s,

330
00:11:53,490 --> 00:11:55,890
the conversation about
psychedelics and meditation

331
00:11:55,890 --> 00:11:57,543
was sort of one and the same.

332
00:11:58,620 --> 00:12:02,790
That changed in the late
1980s and early 1990s

333
00:12:02,790 --> 00:12:04,350
when people like Jon Kabat-Zinn

334
00:12:04,350 --> 00:12:07,260
started writing books that
were purely about meditation

335
00:12:07,260 --> 00:12:10,050
and suggesting that people
explore meditative practices

336
00:12:10,050 --> 00:12:11,850
for the utility to bring calmness,

337
00:12:11,850 --> 00:12:14,910
adjust stress, improve sleep, et cetera,

338
00:12:14,910 --> 00:12:17,490
divorced from the conversation
about psychedelics.

339
00:12:17,490 --> 00:12:19,650
Now, that's not to say that
the scientific community

340
00:12:19,650 --> 00:12:22,320
immediately embraced the
conversation about meditation.

341
00:12:22,320 --> 00:12:24,720
In fact, it took quite a long while

342
00:12:24,720 --> 00:12:27,180
for schools like Harvard and Stanford

343
00:12:27,180 --> 00:12:28,800
and other universities around the world

344
00:12:28,800 --> 00:12:33,060
to start embracing and
funding studies of meditation,

345
00:12:33,060 --> 00:12:35,100
asking what sorts of
brain areas are involved,

346
00:12:35,100 --> 00:12:36,360
how it changes the body,

347
00:12:36,360 --> 00:12:37,980
and, perhaps most importantly,

348
00:12:37,980 --> 00:12:40,590
how a meditation practice
can shift the brain and body

349
00:12:40,590 --> 00:12:42,630
when somebody is finished meditating

350
00:12:42,630 --> 00:12:45,750
and is off in their life
doing their everyday things.

351
00:12:45,750 --> 00:12:49,740
In the late 1980s and
especially within the 1990s,

352
00:12:49,740 --> 00:12:51,480
the advent of brain imaging technology

353
00:12:51,480 --> 00:12:54,240
like magnetic residence imaging, MRI,

354
00:12:54,240 --> 00:12:56,100
or functional magnetic residence imaging

355
00:12:56,100 --> 00:12:59,610
was a way to look at the
brain while it was active,

356
00:12:59,610 --> 00:13:01,440
not just to get an image of its structure,

357
00:13:01,440 --> 00:13:02,730
but also how it's functioning

358
00:13:02,730 --> 00:13:04,530
in the areas that so-called light up.

359
00:13:04,530 --> 00:13:07,620
When all of that technology
became accessible and popular,

360
00:13:07,620 --> 00:13:09,780
well, that allowed a large
number of laboratories

361
00:13:09,780 --> 00:13:12,540
to start asking how specific patterns

362
00:13:12,540 --> 00:13:14,040
of thinking and breathing,

363
00:13:14,040 --> 00:13:15,750
maybe people sitting
in the lotus position,

364
00:13:15,750 --> 00:13:16,680
but more often than that,

365
00:13:16,680 --> 00:13:19,080
it would be people inside of an MRI magnet

366
00:13:19,080 --> 00:13:19,950
because it is a magnet,

367
00:13:19,950 --> 00:13:21,180
they sort of put you into a little tube

368
00:13:21,180 --> 00:13:24,540
and push you into the tube, not
against your will of course,

369
00:13:24,540 --> 00:13:27,180
but put people into the
tube, have them meditate,

370
00:13:27,180 --> 00:13:29,070
and then look at how the brain changed

371
00:13:29,070 --> 00:13:30,600
and to do that over time.

372
00:13:30,600 --> 00:13:32,100
When those studies were done,

373
00:13:32,100 --> 00:13:35,700
what was discovered was really
quite miraculous, really.

374
00:13:35,700 --> 00:13:37,680
And now we don't think
of it as surprising,

375
00:13:37,680 --> 00:13:38,940
but what was discovered

376
00:13:38,940 --> 00:13:41,790
was a huge laundry list of brain changes.

377
00:13:41,790 --> 00:13:45,270
And then when people were
evaluated in their outside life,

378
00:13:45,270 --> 00:13:47,130
so when they would fill out reports

379
00:13:47,130 --> 00:13:48,810
of their subjective feelings of happiness

380
00:13:48,810 --> 00:13:50,070
or they would report their sleep,

381
00:13:50,070 --> 00:13:52,410
or even if objective measures were taken

382
00:13:52,410 --> 00:13:53,760
like changes in hormones

383
00:13:53,760 --> 00:13:56,280
or markers of inflammation, et cetera,

384
00:13:56,280 --> 00:14:00,270
a large list of information
fell out of that

385
00:14:00,270 --> 00:14:03,060
which revealed that indeed there are many,

386
00:14:03,060 --> 00:14:05,760
a dozen or more clear benefits

387
00:14:05,760 --> 00:14:07,650
of a regular meditation practice,

388
00:14:07,650 --> 00:14:10,950
and some of those meditation
practices could be quite short.

389
00:14:10,950 --> 00:14:12,800
So nowadays, we think of meditation

390
00:14:12,800 --> 00:14:14,220
as pretty commonly accepted,

391
00:14:14,220 --> 00:14:16,830
and in fact, that has a
lot to do with the fact

392
00:14:16,830 --> 00:14:19,050
that many of the major tech companies

393
00:14:19,050 --> 00:14:23,220
in the Bay Area during the
2000s such as Google and Apple

394
00:14:23,220 --> 00:14:25,680
and any number of different
social media companies

395
00:14:25,680 --> 00:14:28,170
and other companies and
business ventures, et cetera,

396
00:14:28,170 --> 00:14:30,600
and investment firms all over the world

397
00:14:30,600 --> 00:14:33,090
started hiring people to train meditation

398
00:14:33,090 --> 00:14:35,580
or had online courses for meditation.

399
00:14:35,580 --> 00:14:37,860
So nowadays, we think of
meditation as this thing

400
00:14:37,860 --> 00:14:41,220
that almost everybody
understands can benefit us,

401
00:14:41,220 --> 00:14:44,280
but we now sit at an interesting frontier

402
00:14:44,280 --> 00:14:47,550
where most people think of
meditation as one thing,

403
00:14:47,550 --> 00:14:48,810
sort of like the word exercise,

404
00:14:48,810 --> 00:14:50,370
which, of course, could
mean weight training,

405
00:14:50,370 --> 00:14:51,203
it could mean running,

406
00:14:51,203 --> 00:14:53,430
it could mean high-intensity
interval training,

407
00:14:53,430 --> 00:14:56,940
all of which, as you know,
will get you different results

408
00:14:56,940 --> 00:14:59,070
depending on what you
do, how often you do it,

409
00:14:59,070 --> 00:15:01,770
and the specifics of what you actually do.

410
00:15:01,770 --> 00:15:05,550
So, too, meditation can give
you very specific results.

411
00:15:05,550 --> 00:15:08,450
It can give you more focus,
it can give you better sleep,

412
00:15:08,450 --> 00:15:10,140
it can give you a combination of results

413
00:15:10,140 --> 00:15:13,050
just like exercise can
depending on the exercise.

414
00:15:13,050 --> 00:15:14,610
So what we are going to talk about next

415
00:15:14,610 --> 00:15:17,400
is the specific changes
that happen in the brain

416
00:15:17,400 --> 00:15:19,680
with specific aspects of meditation.

417
00:15:19,680 --> 00:15:22,200
That is, what happens
when you close your eyes,

418
00:15:22,200 --> 00:15:24,930
what happens when you
focus your attention inward

419
00:15:24,930 --> 00:15:26,580
versus focusing your attention outward

420
00:15:26,580 --> 00:15:27,990
because, as I mentioned before,

421
00:15:27,990 --> 00:15:29,850
there's third eye meditation
where you close your eyes

422
00:15:29,850 --> 00:15:32,130
and focus on that spot
just behind your forehead

423
00:15:32,130 --> 00:15:33,600
and you focus on your breathing.

424
00:15:33,600 --> 00:15:35,130
There's also meditation practices

425
00:15:35,130 --> 00:15:36,630
where you're focusing
on what you're eating

426
00:15:36,630 --> 00:15:38,280
with a lot of so-called mindfulness,

427
00:15:38,280 --> 00:15:40,170
being very present to
whatever's happening,

428
00:15:40,170 --> 00:15:41,610
not letting your mind wander

429
00:15:41,610 --> 00:15:43,830
or think about yesterday or tomorrow

430
00:15:43,830 --> 00:15:44,880
or what's happening next,

431
00:15:44,880 --> 00:15:47,250
but really focusing on the present.

432
00:15:47,250 --> 00:15:49,440
There are also meditation
practices, of course,

433
00:15:49,440 --> 00:15:52,770
where you are in a format of
interpersonal communication

434
00:15:52,770 --> 00:15:54,840
where you're really
listening very intensely.

435
00:15:54,840 --> 00:15:56,640
That, too, is a form of mindfulness.

436
00:15:56,640 --> 00:15:58,320
So we're going to parse
each of these things,

437
00:15:58,320 --> 00:15:59,460
and we are going to ask

438
00:15:59,460 --> 00:16:00,900
what's happening in the brain and body

439
00:16:00,900 --> 00:16:03,000
during each of these meditation practices

440
00:16:03,000 --> 00:16:05,910
so that you can develop
specific meditation practices

441
00:16:05,910 --> 00:16:09,300
that you can invoke in your
real life on a daily basis

442
00:16:09,300 --> 00:16:13,140
or, thankfully, I would say,
for some who are pretty busy,

443
00:16:13,140 --> 00:16:15,930
that you could even do once
a week or even once a month

444
00:16:15,930 --> 00:16:19,380
that will still clearly
benefit you in specific ways.

445
00:16:19,380 --> 00:16:21,510
I'd like to spend the
next 10 minutes or so

446
00:16:21,510 --> 00:16:23,817
talking about the
neuroscience of meditation,

447
00:16:23,817 --> 00:16:26,040
and I promise you I'm not
going to just list off

448
00:16:26,040 --> 00:16:27,270
a bunch of different brain areas

449
00:16:27,270 --> 00:16:28,710
that are active during meditation.

450
00:16:28,710 --> 00:16:29,760
That wouldn't be useful to you.

451
00:16:29,760 --> 00:16:31,110
In fact, I don't believe

452
00:16:31,110 --> 00:16:32,910
in throwing out a lot of nomenclature

453
00:16:32,910 --> 00:16:35,880
without also giving some
mechanistic explanation

454
00:16:35,880 --> 00:16:37,857
as to what different brain areas do.

455
00:16:37,857 --> 00:16:39,990
And you could say, "Well,
what good is it knowing

456
00:16:39,990 --> 00:16:41,820
what different brain
areas do and their names

457
00:16:41,820 --> 00:16:43,980
if I can't actually
manipulate those brain areas?"

458
00:16:43,980 --> 00:16:44,813
But the good news

459
00:16:44,813 --> 00:16:47,370
is you actually can
manipulate those brain areas.

460
00:16:47,370 --> 00:16:48,240
As I'll tell you today,

461
00:16:48,240 --> 00:16:51,330
you can turn up the activity
in certain brain areas

462
00:16:51,330 --> 00:16:54,060
and turn down the activity
in specific brain areas

463
00:16:54,060 --> 00:16:56,880
with specific elements
of a meditation practice,

464
00:16:56,880 --> 00:16:59,310
so that's quite exciting
and quite different really

465
00:16:59,310 --> 00:17:00,960
from other aspects of neuroscience

466
00:17:00,960 --> 00:17:03,150
that we might discuss on this podcast.

467
00:17:03,150 --> 00:17:05,130
So there are a few different brain areas

468
00:17:05,130 --> 00:17:07,230
whose names I'd like to arm you with.

469
00:17:07,230 --> 00:17:10,260
And again, the names
themselves aren't essential,

470
00:17:10,260 --> 00:17:12,300
but if you can grasp even the top contour

471
00:17:12,300 --> 00:17:13,260
of what I'm about to say,

472
00:17:13,260 --> 00:17:14,579
you'll be in a much better position

473
00:17:14,579 --> 00:17:16,879
to parse and use the
information that follows.

474
00:17:18,180 --> 00:17:19,410
There's an area of your brain

475
00:17:19,410 --> 00:17:21,300
that sits right behind your forehead

476
00:17:21,300 --> 00:17:23,280
that's called the prefrontal cortex.

477
00:17:23,280 --> 00:17:25,650
Basically, it's the
front bumper of your head

478
00:17:25,650 --> 00:17:27,690
just behind the bone, okay?

479
00:17:27,690 --> 00:17:29,010
That area just behind your forehead

480
00:17:29,010 --> 00:17:30,720
that we call the prefrontal cortex

481
00:17:30,720 --> 00:17:32,910
actually encompasses a
lot of different things.

482
00:17:32,910 --> 00:17:34,800
And actually, you have two of them.

483
00:17:34,800 --> 00:17:36,480
You have one on the
right side of your brain

484
00:17:36,480 --> 00:17:38,280
and you have one on the
left side of your brain,

485
00:17:38,280 --> 00:17:39,510
and they're connected to one another

486
00:17:39,510 --> 00:17:41,430
but they actually do different things.

487
00:17:41,430 --> 00:17:44,100
The area that I'd like to
focus on today for a bit

488
00:17:44,100 --> 00:17:46,980
is the so-called left prefrontal cortex,

489
00:17:46,980 --> 00:17:48,840
or if we were going to
get really specific,

490
00:17:48,840 --> 00:17:51,690
we'd say the left dorsolateral
prefrontal cortex.

491
00:17:51,690 --> 00:17:54,450
Dorsal means up, lateral
means to the side,

492
00:17:54,450 --> 00:17:56,520
so if you want to touch
the left side of your head

493
00:17:56,520 --> 00:17:58,860
and move your hand just
toward the midline,

494
00:17:58,860 --> 00:18:01,050
toward the sort of top of
your head a little bit,

495
00:18:01,050 --> 00:18:03,060
so that's dorsal, and then lateral,

496
00:18:03,060 --> 00:18:04,620
as long as your hand is still
on the side of your head,

497
00:18:04,620 --> 00:18:07,650
you're in the left dorsolateral
prefrontal cortex, okay?

498
00:18:07,650 --> 00:18:09,660
So you've got your hand
probably right over

499
00:18:09,660 --> 00:18:12,540
your left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex.

500
00:18:12,540 --> 00:18:15,300
That area of the brain, we
know from lesion studies

501
00:18:15,300 --> 00:18:17,670
where it's been damaged
in animals or humans

502
00:18:17,670 --> 00:18:19,920
and we know from stimulation studies

503
00:18:19,920 --> 00:18:23,130
where it's been selectively
stimulated in animals,

504
00:18:23,130 --> 00:18:26,820
or yes, indeed, also
it's been done in humans,

505
00:18:26,820 --> 00:18:31,470
has an incredible ability to
control your bodily senses

506
00:18:31,470 --> 00:18:35,340
and to make sense, that is,
to interpret what's going on

507
00:18:35,340 --> 00:18:38,490
in terms of your emotions
and your bodily sensations.

508
00:18:38,490 --> 00:18:40,830
So from now on, unless I say otherwise,

509
00:18:40,830 --> 00:18:43,740
if I say prefrontal cortex,
I'm specifically referring

510
00:18:43,740 --> 00:18:45,990
to the left dorsolateral
prefrontal cortex,

511
00:18:45,990 --> 00:18:47,130
but I'm going to shorten that up

512
00:18:47,130 --> 00:18:49,980
just for sake of simplicity
and ease of communication.

513
00:18:49,980 --> 00:18:52,080
If I'm going to talk about
another area of prefrontal cortex,

514
00:18:52,080 --> 00:18:53,190
I'll talk about another area,

515
00:18:53,190 --> 00:18:54,990
but if I say prefrontal cortex today,

516
00:18:54,990 --> 00:18:57,960
what I mean is left
dorsolateral prefrontal cortex.

517
00:18:57,960 --> 00:19:00,780
Stimulation of left
dorsolateral prefrontal cortex

518
00:19:00,780 --> 00:19:02,520
or, I should say more appropriately,

519
00:19:02,520 --> 00:19:06,363
when your left dorsolateral
prefrontal cortex is active,

520
00:19:07,530 --> 00:19:09,990
you are in a great position

521
00:19:09,990 --> 00:19:13,260
to interpret what's going
on with you emotionally,

522
00:19:13,260 --> 00:19:17,580
to interpret your bodily signals
of comfort or discomfort,

523
00:19:17,580 --> 00:19:19,380
and then to make really good decisions

524
00:19:19,380 --> 00:19:22,320
on the basis of that interpretation.

525
00:19:22,320 --> 00:19:26,010
And that's because the left
dorsolateral prefrontal cortex

526
00:19:26,010 --> 00:19:27,960
is in direct communication with

527
00:19:27,960 --> 00:19:31,650
and is directly connected
to another brain area

528
00:19:31,650 --> 00:19:35,040
called the anterior
cingulate cortex, or ACC.

529
00:19:35,040 --> 00:19:38,520
Now, I'm just going to refer
to it as the ACC, okay?

530
00:19:38,520 --> 00:19:41,340
The ACC is an area of your brain

531
00:19:41,340 --> 00:19:43,350
that is interpreting a
lot of different things

532
00:19:43,350 --> 00:19:44,730
about bodily signals,

533
00:19:44,730 --> 00:19:47,313
for instance, how fast you're breathing,

534
00:19:48,300 --> 00:19:51,900
whether or not your heart is
beating quickly or slowly,

535
00:19:51,900 --> 00:19:53,040
and, more importantly,

536
00:19:53,040 --> 00:19:55,530
whether or not your heart
is beating quickly or slowly

537
00:19:55,530 --> 00:19:57,660
for the circumstance that you are in.

538
00:19:57,660 --> 00:19:59,520
So for instance, if
you're running up a hill

539
00:19:59,520 --> 00:20:02,040
and you're even in great shape

540
00:20:02,040 --> 00:20:04,080
and your heart is beating very fast,

541
00:20:04,080 --> 00:20:06,870
it's unlikely that you
are going to be concerned

542
00:20:06,870 --> 00:20:08,550
about your heart beating fast

543
00:20:08,550 --> 00:20:10,800
because that is appropriate
for the circumstance.

544
00:20:10,800 --> 00:20:12,690
However, if you're just walking along

545
00:20:12,690 --> 00:20:14,520
and all of a sudden, your heart
starts beating very quickly

546
00:20:14,520 --> 00:20:17,520
for no apparent reason,

547
00:20:17,520 --> 00:20:19,500
well, then you are going to interpret that

548
00:20:19,500 --> 00:20:23,100
as either pathologic or uncomfortable,

549
00:20:23,100 --> 00:20:26,193
inappropriate for the context
that you happen to be in.

550
00:20:27,630 --> 00:20:30,090
The left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex

551
00:20:30,090 --> 00:20:31,080
is the area of the brain

552
00:20:31,080 --> 00:20:33,480
that actually has some control over

553
00:20:33,480 --> 00:20:35,490
and especially can interpret

554
00:20:35,490 --> 00:20:38,700
what's going on in this ACC region.

555
00:20:38,700 --> 00:20:41,190
Now, most of you probably
haven't heard of the ACC.

556
00:20:41,190 --> 00:20:43,500
Most of you probably have
heard of a brain area

557
00:20:43,500 --> 00:20:44,340
called the amygdala.

558
00:20:44,340 --> 00:20:45,750
It's an almond-shaped structure

559
00:20:45,750 --> 00:20:46,800
on the two sides of the brain,

560
00:20:46,800 --> 00:20:49,140
people talk about it as
the fear center, et cetera.

561
00:20:49,140 --> 00:20:52,230
But your ACC, the
anterior cingulate cortex,

562
00:20:52,230 --> 00:20:54,240
gets input from areas like the amygdala,

563
00:20:54,240 --> 00:20:55,380
your threat detection centers,

564
00:20:55,380 --> 00:20:58,650
but it also gets input
from an enormous number

565
00:20:58,650 --> 00:21:00,510
of other areas of your brain and body,

566
00:21:00,510 --> 00:21:03,900
including your heart, your gut,

567
00:21:03,900 --> 00:21:06,750
so it gets information about how full,

568
00:21:06,750 --> 00:21:09,690
that is, distended, or
how empty your gut is.

569
00:21:09,690 --> 00:21:11,970
It gets information about
how quickly you're breathing

570
00:21:11,970 --> 00:21:16,470
from input from your lungs
and related structures.

571
00:21:16,470 --> 00:21:18,990
It's an absolutely critical station

572
00:21:18,990 --> 00:21:21,240
for making sense of what's
going on in your body,

573
00:21:21,240 --> 00:21:24,087
and it works very closely
along with one other structure.

574
00:21:24,087 --> 00:21:26,520
And I promise this is going
to be the third structure

575
00:21:26,520 --> 00:21:28,980
in this triad, and then
I'll stop listing off names.

576
00:21:28,980 --> 00:21:30,510
So we have dorsolateral prefrontal cortex.

577
00:21:30,510 --> 00:21:31,980
Think of that as sort of the interpreter

578
00:21:31,980 --> 00:21:33,900
of what's going on inside of you.

579
00:21:33,900 --> 00:21:36,900
You have the ACC, or
anterior cingulate cortex,

580
00:21:36,900 --> 00:21:38,100
which is the area of your brain

581
00:21:38,100 --> 00:21:40,110
that's bringing in all this information

582
00:21:40,110 --> 00:21:42,270
about what's going on inside your body

583
00:21:42,270 --> 00:21:43,980
and even on the surface of your body.

584
00:21:43,980 --> 00:21:45,690
You know, if you have any pain or an itch

585
00:21:45,690 --> 00:21:47,310
or a mosquito bite on
the surface of your body,

586
00:21:47,310 --> 00:21:49,912
your ACC would definitely register that.

587
00:21:49,912 --> 00:21:50,790
And then there's this other

588
00:21:50,790 --> 00:21:52,440
absolutely incredible brain structure

589
00:21:52,440 --> 00:21:55,800
which is called the insula,
I-N-S-U-L-A, insula,

590
00:21:55,800 --> 00:21:58,140
and the insula has a bunch
of different parts to it.

591
00:21:58,140 --> 00:22:02,400
But the insula is another area
that is interpreting signals

592
00:22:02,400 --> 00:22:05,220
of what's going on in your brain and body,

593
00:22:05,220 --> 00:22:07,350
so the ACC and the insula
are working together

594
00:22:07,350 --> 00:22:10,290
to try and figure out, you
know, what's going on inside me?

595
00:22:10,290 --> 00:22:11,700
And in addition to that,

596
00:22:11,700 --> 00:22:13,770
the insula is interpreting information

597
00:22:13,770 --> 00:22:16,290
about what's going on outside of you.

598
00:22:16,290 --> 00:22:18,603
So your insula is saying, for instance,

599
00:22:18,603 --> 00:22:20,940
hey, this is a steep
hill that I'm running up,

600
00:22:20,940 --> 00:22:22,290
and as a consequence,

601
00:22:22,290 --> 00:22:24,810
whatever heart rate increase
that I'm experiencing

602
00:22:24,810 --> 00:22:26,730
or heavy breathing or burning in my lungs,

603
00:22:26,730 --> 00:22:27,900
this all makes sense.

604
00:22:27,900 --> 00:22:29,640
I don't have to be worried,
I don't have to be scared.

605
00:22:29,640 --> 00:22:32,130
I might want to slow down,
but this makes sense.

606
00:22:32,130 --> 00:22:34,860
Whereas, for instance, in the
example I previously gave,

607
00:22:34,860 --> 00:22:36,480
where if you're sitting in a room

608
00:22:36,480 --> 00:22:38,130
and everything is pretty calm,

609
00:22:38,130 --> 00:22:40,650
and all of a sudden, you start
feeling really uncomfortable,

610
00:22:40,650 --> 00:22:42,000
like your stomach doesn't feel right

611
00:22:42,000 --> 00:22:43,130
or you start breathing quickly

612
00:22:43,130 --> 00:22:46,380
or you start having a so-called
anxiety or panic attack,

613
00:22:46,380 --> 00:22:48,840
in large part, that's because the shift

614
00:22:48,840 --> 00:22:51,390
in your bodily sensations doesn't match

615
00:22:51,390 --> 00:22:54,270
or doesn't correspond to
something in the outside world.

616
00:22:54,270 --> 00:22:55,950
So there's this incredible triad

617
00:22:55,950 --> 00:22:58,800
which includes the left
dorsolateral prefrontal cortex,

618
00:22:58,800 --> 00:23:01,950
the cingulate or anterior
cingulate cortex, and the insula,

619
00:23:01,950 --> 00:23:03,960
and those three are working together

620
00:23:03,960 --> 00:23:05,220
in a kind of conversation,

621
00:23:05,220 --> 00:23:08,130
it's a neural conversation,
but a conversation nonetheless,

622
00:23:08,130 --> 00:23:10,740
trying to figure out, okay,
what's going on inside me?

623
00:23:10,740 --> 00:23:13,170
How do I feel? What am I thinking about?

624
00:23:13,170 --> 00:23:14,640
And this could be thoughts about the past

625
00:23:14,640 --> 00:23:16,143
or the future or the present.

626
00:23:17,070 --> 00:23:19,170
They are also in a conversation

627
00:23:19,170 --> 00:23:21,180
as to whether or not the sensations

628
00:23:21,180 --> 00:23:22,710
that you're experiencing,

629
00:23:22,710 --> 00:23:24,390
meaning how quick your breathing is

630
00:23:24,390 --> 00:23:25,920
or how slow your breathing is,

631
00:23:25,920 --> 00:23:29,040
how your heart feels, how your skin feels,

632
00:23:29,040 --> 00:23:32,640
any sensations of pain, or
pleasure for that matter,

633
00:23:32,640 --> 00:23:35,040
whether or not that makes sense
for the situation you're in

634
00:23:35,040 --> 00:23:36,030
and trying to determine

635
00:23:36,030 --> 00:23:38,670
whether or not you are
doing the right things

636
00:23:38,670 --> 00:23:41,340
as a consequence of those sensations.

637
00:23:41,340 --> 00:23:44,220
Okay, so again, if you
can't remember the names

638
00:23:44,220 --> 00:23:45,990
of these different neural
structures in the brain,

639
00:23:45,990 --> 00:23:46,890
don't worry about it.

640
00:23:46,890 --> 00:23:48,360
It's really not that critical.

641
00:23:48,360 --> 00:23:50,640
What is critical is that you understand

642
00:23:50,640 --> 00:23:53,970
that there's a conversation
that's constantly occurring

643
00:23:53,970 --> 00:23:55,740
as long as you are awake

644
00:23:55,740 --> 00:23:59,100
trying to figure out what's
going on inside of you

645
00:23:59,100 --> 00:24:00,420
and whether or not it makes sense

646
00:24:00,420 --> 00:24:03,570
relative to what's going
on outside and around you.

647
00:24:03,570 --> 00:24:04,920
Now, humans are smart.

648
00:24:04,920 --> 00:24:08,820
That is, we are, to some
extent, conscious of the fact

649
00:24:08,820 --> 00:24:13,290
that we have memories of the
past, awareness of the present,

650
00:24:13,290 --> 00:24:15,390
and anticipation of the future.

651
00:24:15,390 --> 00:24:17,340
So we do realize, for instance,

652
00:24:17,340 --> 00:24:20,130
that we can be seated at
the dinner table, excuse me,

653
00:24:20,130 --> 00:24:22,860
and have a thought about
something tomorrow,

654
00:24:22,860 --> 00:24:24,960
maybe an exam that's stressing us out

655
00:24:24,960 --> 00:24:25,793
or something like that,

656
00:24:25,793 --> 00:24:27,990
and that will change our bodily state

657
00:24:27,990 --> 00:24:29,850
in a way that is not optimal

658
00:24:29,850 --> 00:24:31,590
for what we're doing in the moment

659
00:24:31,590 --> 00:24:33,090
but that can still make sense to us

660
00:24:33,090 --> 00:24:34,440
because that exam is important,

661
00:24:34,440 --> 00:24:35,670
maybe we're feeling some pressure

662
00:24:35,670 --> 00:24:37,350
about a hard conversation we have to have,

663
00:24:37,350 --> 00:24:40,020
or maybe we are very
excited about the next day

664
00:24:40,020 --> 00:24:42,480
and we can't eat because we're so excited,

665
00:24:42,480 --> 00:24:43,860
and that can make perfect sense to us

666
00:24:43,860 --> 00:24:47,160
because we do have access
to this knowledge about self

667
00:24:47,160 --> 00:24:48,930
that we can think about the past,

668
00:24:48,930 --> 00:24:50,610
the present, or the future.

669
00:24:50,610 --> 00:24:53,880
So that makes the conversation
these three structures are in

670
00:24:53,880 --> 00:24:55,890
even more interesting and dynamic

671
00:24:55,890 --> 00:24:59,850
because what it means is that
we can be doing something,

672
00:24:59,850 --> 00:25:02,310
eating, talking, running,

673
00:25:02,310 --> 00:25:04,440
any number of different activities,

674
00:25:04,440 --> 00:25:09,120
and our bodily state may or
may not match what we are doing

675
00:25:09,120 --> 00:25:11,580
in a way that's adaptive for that,

676
00:25:11,580 --> 00:25:13,010
and yet that can be completely okay

677
00:25:13,010 --> 00:25:16,470
or at least understandable for us.

678
00:25:16,470 --> 00:25:19,860
Now, a major emphasis
of a meditation practice

679
00:25:19,860 --> 00:25:23,100
is to make us so-called more mindful.

680
00:25:23,100 --> 00:25:24,060
What is mindfulness?

681
00:25:24,060 --> 00:25:25,680
Well, again, there isn't one perfect

682
00:25:25,680 --> 00:25:29,340
universally accepted operational
definition of mindfulness.

683
00:25:29,340 --> 00:25:30,480
That's basically nerd speak

684
00:25:30,480 --> 00:25:33,930
for saying people can't agree
exactly what mindfulness

685
00:25:33,930 --> 00:25:38,100
should be, is, and means for everyone.

686
00:25:38,100 --> 00:25:40,620
But most people assume, and I think agree,

687
00:25:40,620 --> 00:25:44,880
that mindfulness includes
something about being present.

688
00:25:44,880 --> 00:25:45,930
And when I say present,

689
00:25:45,930 --> 00:25:48,660
that doesn't necessarily mean
present to one's surroundings

690
00:25:48,660 --> 00:25:50,820
because of course a lot
of meditation practices

691
00:25:50,820 --> 00:25:53,190
that are designed to make
us more mindful and present

692
00:25:53,190 --> 00:25:54,840
are designed to make us
more mindful and present

693
00:25:54,840 --> 00:25:56,550
to what's happening internally

694
00:25:56,550 --> 00:25:59,970
while ignoring everything
that's happening externally,

695
00:25:59,970 --> 00:26:02,370
but they are designed
to make us more present

696
00:26:02,370 --> 00:26:03,810
to our bodily sensations

697
00:26:03,810 --> 00:26:06,690
and, in particular, our
breathing and our thoughts

698
00:26:06,690 --> 00:26:07,980
in the moment.

699
00:26:07,980 --> 00:26:09,450
So let's now explore

700
00:26:09,450 --> 00:26:11,610
what a generic meditation
practice looks like,

701
00:26:11,610 --> 00:26:15,090
and let's evaluate how that
tends to change the activity

702
00:26:15,090 --> 00:26:16,920
of these neural circuits
in the brain and body.

703
00:26:16,920 --> 00:26:19,500
And then from there, we
can split the conversation

704
00:26:19,500 --> 00:26:21,120
into a couple of different bins,

705
00:26:21,120 --> 00:26:24,000
that is, meditation
practices that are ideal

706
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:25,680
for enhancing focus,

707
00:26:25,680 --> 00:26:28,890
meditation practices that
are ideal for improving mood,

708
00:26:28,890 --> 00:26:32,520
meditation practices that are
ideal for improving sleep,

709
00:26:32,520 --> 00:26:36,090
and meditation practices
that, believe it or not,

710
00:26:36,090 --> 00:26:39,090
benefit all of those
things in one fell swoop.

711
00:26:39,090 --> 00:26:41,310
Okay, so what happens
during a meditation practice

712
00:26:41,310 --> 00:26:42,900
at the neural level?

713
00:26:42,900 --> 00:26:44,610
In order to answer that question,

714
00:26:44,610 --> 00:26:45,960
we are going to be scientists.

715
00:26:45,960 --> 00:26:48,510
That means you and I are
going to be scientists now.

716
00:26:48,510 --> 00:26:50,490
We are going to break down a practice

717
00:26:50,490 --> 00:26:53,040
into its different component parts

718
00:26:53,040 --> 00:26:56,160
and address what we know for sure

719
00:26:56,160 --> 00:26:59,070
about the brain activation
states that occur

720
00:26:59,070 --> 00:27:00,750
with those different component parts.

721
00:27:00,750 --> 00:27:01,583
In order to do that,

722
00:27:01,583 --> 00:27:03,960
let's use a somewhat
generic form of meditation,

723
00:27:03,960 --> 00:27:06,390
but it's generic and pretty far-reaching

724
00:27:06,390 --> 00:27:09,540
because I would say that for most people,

725
00:27:09,540 --> 00:27:12,300
about 75%, let's say,

726
00:27:12,300 --> 00:27:15,600
a meditation practice is
going to involve stopping,

727
00:27:15,600 --> 00:27:20,600
meaning getting out of
motion, sitting or lying down,

728
00:27:21,510 --> 00:27:24,120
and, in most cases, closing one's eyes,

729
00:27:24,120 --> 00:27:27,030
although it is absolutely not required

730
00:27:27,030 --> 00:27:28,680
to close one's eyes during meditation.

731
00:27:28,680 --> 00:27:32,280
There are many forms of meditation
that are done eyes open.

732
00:27:32,280 --> 00:27:33,210
But for most people,

733
00:27:33,210 --> 00:27:35,730
it's going to involve
stopping our movement,

734
00:27:35,730 --> 00:27:38,130
that is, not ambulating,
not walking or running,

735
00:27:38,130 --> 00:27:42,120
so seated or lying down with eyes closed.

736
00:27:42,120 --> 00:27:42,960
When we do that,

737
00:27:42,960 --> 00:27:46,110
meaning when we sit or lie
down and close our eyes,

738
00:27:46,110 --> 00:27:48,840
as trivial as that shift
might sound to you,

739
00:27:48,840 --> 00:27:52,740
it actually is a profound shift
in the way that your brain

740
00:27:52,740 --> 00:27:55,980
and other neural circuits
in your body function

741
00:27:55,980 --> 00:27:57,930
for the following reason.

742
00:27:57,930 --> 00:28:00,120
When we close our eyes,

743
00:28:00,120 --> 00:28:05,120
we shut down a major avenue of
what's called exteroception.

744
00:28:05,400 --> 00:28:07,080
What do I mean by exteroception?

745
00:28:07,080 --> 00:28:11,640
Well, very briefly, we are
sensing things on our body

746
00:28:11,640 --> 00:28:13,260
and in our body all the time.

747
00:28:13,260 --> 00:28:15,930
We are also sensing things from
outside of us all the time,

748
00:28:15,930 --> 00:28:18,930
so these could be sights or
sounds, touch on our body,

749
00:28:18,930 --> 00:28:21,480
sensations withinside our body, et cetera.

750
00:28:21,480 --> 00:28:25,050
Now, sensation is distinct
from what we call perception.

751
00:28:25,050 --> 00:28:28,680
Perception is, put simply,

752
00:28:28,680 --> 00:28:32,100
the sensations that we happen
to be paying attention to.

753
00:28:32,100 --> 00:28:35,010
So at any given moment, you
are sensing many, many things.

754
00:28:35,010 --> 00:28:36,480
There are sound waves hitting your ears,

755
00:28:36,480 --> 00:28:38,880
there are pressure receptors
on the bottoms of your feet

756
00:28:38,880 --> 00:28:42,000
sensing your shoes or your
sandals or the floor, et cetera,

757
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:43,440
but you're not perceiving them

758
00:28:43,440 --> 00:28:45,870
until you place your attention on them.

759
00:28:45,870 --> 00:28:48,630
Now, the way perception works

760
00:28:48,630 --> 00:28:51,570
is that you have so-called
spotlights of attention.

761
00:28:51,570 --> 00:28:55,260
You can't perceive everything all at once,

762
00:28:55,260 --> 00:28:57,240
every sound, every sight, every touch.

763
00:28:57,240 --> 00:28:59,670
That would be overwhelming. In
fact, that would be terrible.

764
00:28:59,670 --> 00:29:02,550
Rather you have spotlights of perception

765
00:29:02,550 --> 00:29:04,530
that can either be very narrow,

766
00:29:04,530 --> 00:29:05,363
so for instance,

767
00:29:05,363 --> 00:29:07,620
you could focus all of
your perception right now

768
00:29:07,620 --> 00:29:09,720
on your big toe of your right foot

769
00:29:09,720 --> 00:29:13,800
and really pour all of your
awareness, your attention

770
00:29:13,800 --> 00:29:16,380
into what you're perceiving
there, what it feels like,

771
00:29:16,380 --> 00:29:19,980
if there's tingling or pressure,
heat or cold, et cetera,

772
00:29:19,980 --> 00:29:23,070
or you can broaden that
spotlight to include both feet

773
00:29:23,070 --> 00:29:24,660
or all your toes on both feet

774
00:29:24,660 --> 00:29:27,900
and then your legs and your
whole body or the entire room.

775
00:29:27,900 --> 00:29:29,430
Perception is like a spotlight,

776
00:29:29,430 --> 00:29:31,770
and I should mention
there are very good data

777
00:29:31,770 --> 00:29:34,620
that we can split our attention into two

778
00:29:34,620 --> 00:29:37,560
but probably not more than two spotlights,

779
00:29:37,560 --> 00:29:40,470
and we can make those
spotlights of perception

780
00:29:40,470 --> 00:29:43,500
either very broad and
diffuse or very narrow.

781
00:29:43,500 --> 00:29:45,030
You can practice this now if you like.

782
00:29:45,030 --> 00:29:48,630
You can pick a spot on the
wall away from you anywhere,

783
00:29:48,630 --> 00:29:50,490
or if you're driving, you
can look at some location,

784
00:29:50,490 --> 00:29:54,150
and you can focus intensely
on one small location,

785
00:29:54,150 --> 00:29:56,040
for instance, a tree in the horizon

786
00:29:56,040 --> 00:29:57,510
or a person on the street

787
00:29:57,510 --> 00:30:00,780
or any number of different
things outside of you,

788
00:30:00,780 --> 00:30:02,340
or you can broaden that spotlight

789
00:30:02,340 --> 00:30:04,350
to include the entire scene at once.

790
00:30:04,350 --> 00:30:07,740
You can also focus a spotlight
of perception on your body,

791
00:30:07,740 --> 00:30:12,150
say on the left upper
portion of your chest.

792
00:30:12,150 --> 00:30:13,740
And of course you can focus

793
00:30:13,740 --> 00:30:15,510
on the left upper portion of your chest

794
00:30:15,510 --> 00:30:16,770
and something outside of you,

795
00:30:16,770 --> 00:30:18,030
you can split your attention

796
00:30:18,030 --> 00:30:20,610
between those two perceptual spotlights.

797
00:30:20,610 --> 00:30:22,320
It's very hard, although not impossible,

798
00:30:22,320 --> 00:30:24,690
to have three perceptual spotlights,

799
00:30:24,690 --> 00:30:27,510
but most people can split to two points

800
00:30:27,510 --> 00:30:30,270
of attention or perception pretty easily.

801
00:30:30,270 --> 00:30:32,700
The other thing that most
people can do pretty easily

802
00:30:32,700 --> 00:30:35,160
is merge those two spotlights

803
00:30:35,160 --> 00:30:37,590
or, rather, to have just
one spotlight of attention.

804
00:30:37,590 --> 00:30:38,430
So you don't always have

805
00:30:38,430 --> 00:30:40,140
to have two spotlights of attention on,

806
00:30:40,140 --> 00:30:41,400
and here, I'm using the word attention

807
00:30:41,400 --> 00:30:43,110
and perception interchangeably.

808
00:30:43,110 --> 00:30:46,020
But you could, for instance,
have two points of attention,

809
00:30:46,020 --> 00:30:47,640
so you're talking to somebody
and you're paying attention

810
00:30:47,640 --> 00:30:50,010
to whether or not somebody's
walking in the door or not,

811
00:30:50,010 --> 00:30:50,910
so that's two,

812
00:30:50,910 --> 00:30:52,380
or you could be completely focused

813
00:30:52,380 --> 00:30:53,460
on the person you're talking to,

814
00:30:53,460 --> 00:30:55,770
or you could be completely
focused on the stomach ache

815
00:30:55,770 --> 00:30:58,620
or the great sensation of hunger
