00:33:41,940 --> 00:33:44,610
Okay, so now if we look at
the example of what happens

887
00:33:44,610 --> 00:33:47,460
when you sit or lie
down and close your eyes

888
00:33:47,460 --> 00:33:49,200
and decide to meditate,

889
00:33:49,200 --> 00:33:50,760
you should immediately realize

890
00:33:50,760 --> 00:33:53,280
that that's a tremendous shift

891
00:33:53,280 --> 00:33:56,010
in your perceptual ability, why?

892
00:33:56,010 --> 00:33:58,200
Because that spotlight of attention,

893
00:33:58,200 --> 00:34:00,150
while it can be oriented

894
00:34:00,150 --> 00:34:02,760
toward, for instance,
what you hear in the room

895
00:34:02,760 --> 00:34:06,120
or maybe the feeling of wind moving trees

896
00:34:06,120 --> 00:34:08,010
in the environment that
you happen to be in,

897
00:34:08,010 --> 00:34:09,600
when we close our eyes,

898
00:34:09,600 --> 00:34:13,440
we shut down one of the major
avenues for sensory input,

899
00:34:13,440 --> 00:34:14,403
which is vision.

900
00:34:15,300 --> 00:34:16,739
And when we do that,

901
00:34:16,739 --> 00:34:19,799
there's a tendency for
those perceptual spotlights

902
00:34:19,800 --> 00:34:23,190
to be focused more so on what happens

903
00:34:23,190 --> 00:34:25,889
at the level of the surface of our skin

904
00:34:25,889 --> 00:34:28,499
and inside of our bodies.

905
00:34:28,500 --> 00:34:31,590
And that informs us about
something very important,

906
00:34:31,590 --> 00:34:33,929
which is that there are actually two axes

907
00:34:33,929 --> 00:34:36,899
or two ends of a continuum of perception.

908
00:34:36,900 --> 00:34:38,489
Up until now, I've been
talking about perception

909
00:34:38,489 --> 00:34:40,109
and intention as kind of the same thing,

910
00:34:40,110 --> 00:34:43,230
and indeed they are, at least
for sake of this conversation,

911
00:34:43,230 --> 00:34:45,420
but within that word perception

912
00:34:45,420 --> 00:34:48,750
or within that word attention,
there's a continuum,

913
00:34:48,750 --> 00:34:51,540
and that continuum has on one end

914
00:34:51,540 --> 00:34:53,760
something called interoception.

915
00:34:53,760 --> 00:34:55,803
Interoception, spelled with an I,

916
00:34:56,760 --> 00:34:58,110
is everything that we sense

917
00:34:58,110 --> 00:35:00,660
at the level of our skin and inward,

918
00:35:00,660 --> 00:35:02,310
so the sensation inside our stomach,

919
00:35:02,310 --> 00:35:03,990
the sensation of our heart beating.

920
00:35:03,990 --> 00:35:06,060
Some people can sense their
heart beating pretty easily.

921
00:35:06,060 --> 00:35:08,523
Other people have more
challenge doing that.

922
00:35:09,630 --> 00:35:11,730
What we are feeling on
the surface of our skin,

923
00:35:11,730 --> 00:35:15,123
how hot or cold we feel,
that's interoception.

924
00:35:16,050 --> 00:35:18,480
In contrast, at the other
end of the continuum

925
00:35:18,480 --> 00:35:21,720
is so-called exteroception,
spelled with an E.

926
00:35:21,720 --> 00:35:24,810
Exteroception is perception of everything

927
00:35:24,810 --> 00:35:28,830
that's outside or beyond
the confines of our skin.

928
00:35:28,830 --> 00:35:30,540
So by shutting our eyes,

929
00:35:30,540 --> 00:35:33,060
and in particular, in
a meditative practice

930
00:35:33,060 --> 00:35:34,740
where we direct our attention

931
00:35:34,740 --> 00:35:36,480
toward our so-called third eye center,

932
00:35:36,480 --> 00:35:38,010
this area right behind our forehead,

933
00:35:38,010 --> 00:35:41,550
which, not so incidentally,
is the prefrontal cortex,

934
00:35:41,550 --> 00:35:44,640
or in some cases where people
will focus on their breathing,

935
00:35:44,640 --> 00:35:46,110
so the movement of their stomach

936
00:35:46,110 --> 00:35:47,460
or the movement of their diaphragm

937
00:35:47,460 --> 00:35:48,780
or the lifting of their chest

938
00:35:48,780 --> 00:35:51,060
or the extension of their
belly while they breathe.

939
00:35:51,060 --> 00:35:52,620
By doing that,

940
00:35:52,620 --> 00:35:56,820
we are taking what ordinarily
is a perceptual state

941
00:35:56,820 --> 00:36:01,230
that's split between the
outside world, exteroception,

942
00:36:01,230 --> 00:36:03,810
and usually also toward our inner state.

943
00:36:03,810 --> 00:36:05,580
You know, most people
are generally in touch

944
00:36:05,580 --> 00:36:07,950
with how they are feeling
from the skin inward

945
00:36:07,950 --> 00:36:09,600
while they are also paying attention

946
00:36:09,600 --> 00:36:11,040
to what's outside of them.

947
00:36:11,040 --> 00:36:11,873
You can think about somebody,

948
00:36:11,873 --> 00:36:14,100
for instance, at a
restaurant or a sandwich shop

949
00:36:14,100 --> 00:36:15,990
about to order a sandwich
and you're reading the menu,

950
00:36:15,990 --> 00:36:17,400
so that's exteroception, right?

951
00:36:17,400 --> 00:36:19,620
The menu is outside the
confines of your skin.

952
00:36:19,620 --> 00:36:22,950
And little ideas or maybe
big ideas come to mind

953
00:36:22,950 --> 00:36:24,330
about what the roast beef sandwich

954
00:36:24,330 --> 00:36:26,730
or the vegetarian
sandwich will taste like,

955
00:36:26,730 --> 00:36:28,290
what it will do for you,

956
00:36:28,290 --> 00:36:31,110
what's in it, what you like,
what you don't like, et cetera.

957
00:36:31,110 --> 00:36:34,620
That's splitting interoception
and exteroception.

958
00:36:34,620 --> 00:36:37,140
But when we close our eyes,
we stop, we slow down,

959
00:36:37,140 --> 00:36:40,320
we focus on our breathing
or that third eye center,

960
00:36:40,320 --> 00:36:44,130
the majority of our perception
then shifts to interoception.

961
00:36:44,130 --> 00:36:45,870
And when we shift down

962
00:36:45,870 --> 00:36:48,900
to that end of the
continuum of interoception,

963
00:36:48,900 --> 00:36:50,970
something very important happens.

964
00:36:50,970 --> 00:36:53,940
What happens is that those two regions,

965
00:36:53,940 --> 00:36:57,450
the ACC, the anterior cingulate
cortex, and the insula,

966
00:36:57,450 --> 00:37:00,450
really ramp up their
levels of neural activity,

967
00:37:00,450 --> 00:37:01,920
and that should make perfect sense to you

968
00:37:01,920 --> 00:37:05,280
because those are areas of
your brain that are registering

969
00:37:05,280 --> 00:37:07,740
and paying attention to
the various sensations

970
00:37:07,740 --> 00:37:10,980
of how full or empty your stomach feels,

971
00:37:10,980 --> 00:37:13,680
whether or not the surface of
your skin feels hot or cold,

972
00:37:13,680 --> 00:37:14,760
and on and on.

973
00:37:14,760 --> 00:37:17,820
So by just sitting down or lying
down and closing your eyes,

974
00:37:17,820 --> 00:37:19,950
your brain undergoes a massive shift

975
00:37:19,950 --> 00:37:22,590
from exteroception to interoception.

976
00:37:22,590 --> 00:37:24,330
Now, that's not to say
you can't be distracted

977
00:37:24,330 --> 00:37:26,640
by external events, and,
in fact, many people are,

978
00:37:26,640 --> 00:37:28,440
but the early stages of transitioning

979
00:37:28,440 --> 00:37:30,150
into a meditative state

980
00:37:30,150 --> 00:37:33,150
involve this shift down the continuum,

981
00:37:33,150 --> 00:37:34,920
or, I should say, to
one end of the continuum

982
00:37:34,920 --> 00:37:38,100
because there's no down-up,
there's just the continuum,

983
00:37:38,100 --> 00:37:39,660
shift along the continuum

984
00:37:39,660 --> 00:37:42,420
to heightened levels of interoception.

985
00:37:42,420 --> 00:37:43,980
Now, I mentioned this briefly before,

986
00:37:43,980 --> 00:37:48,980
but many people are very
interoceptively aware

987
00:37:49,500 --> 00:37:52,440
just naturally, even if they
don't do a meditation practice.

988
00:37:52,440 --> 00:37:54,000
Other people are not.

989
00:37:54,000 --> 00:37:56,040
And there's a pretty good measure

990
00:37:56,040 --> 00:37:57,690
of whether or not you have high levels

991
00:37:57,690 --> 00:38:00,090
of interoceptive awareness or capability,

992
00:38:00,090 --> 00:38:02,460
and that is your ability
to count your heartbeats

993
00:38:02,460 --> 00:38:05,550
without placing your fingers
anywhere with any pressure

994
00:38:05,550 --> 00:38:07,380
to take your pulse.

995
00:38:07,380 --> 00:38:08,520
You can do this if you like,

996
00:38:08,520 --> 00:38:11,130
you can actually try and estimate
your number of heartbeats

997
00:38:11,130 --> 00:38:13,320
simply by trying to feel your heart beat.

998
00:38:13,320 --> 00:38:14,760
Some people are very good,

999
00:38:14,760 --> 00:38:16,680
meaning they're very
accurate at doing this,

1000
00:38:16,680 --> 00:38:17,910
other people are not.

1001
00:38:17,910 --> 00:38:19,680
It does seem to be an ability

1002
00:38:19,680 --> 00:38:21,630
that can be trained up quite a bit,

1003
00:38:21,630 --> 00:38:23,100
and, in fact, meditative practices

1004
00:38:23,100 --> 00:38:25,530
will improve your interoceptive awareness,

1005
00:38:25,530 --> 00:38:28,683
but, and this is a very important point,

1006
00:38:29,580 --> 00:38:31,710
heightened levels of
interoceptive awareness,

1007
00:38:31,710 --> 00:38:33,690
while that might sound attractive,

1008
00:38:33,690 --> 00:38:36,840
oh, to be really in touch with your body,

1009
00:38:36,840 --> 00:38:40,050
that is not always beneficial, why?

1010
00:38:40,050 --> 00:38:41,790
Because many people who, for instance,

1011
00:38:41,790 --> 00:38:44,670
have excessive levels of anxiety

1012
00:38:44,670 --> 00:38:46,770
have excessive levels of anxiety

1013
00:38:46,770 --> 00:38:49,170
because they are very keenly aware

1014
00:38:49,170 --> 00:38:52,050
of any subtle shift in their
heart rate or breathing

1015
00:38:52,050 --> 00:38:55,260
or change in the sensations
within their stomach.

1016
00:38:55,260 --> 00:38:57,060
Whereas other people who are less aware

1017
00:38:57,060 --> 00:39:00,030
of their bodily state, that
can be beneficial, right?

1018
00:39:00,030 --> 00:39:03,000
It can be adaptive or not,
depending on the circumstances.

1019
00:39:03,000 --> 00:39:04,980
It's probably not adaptive

1020
00:39:04,980 --> 00:39:08,280
to be very, very aware
of your internal state

1021
00:39:08,280 --> 00:39:09,960
if, for instance, you're
doing public speaking,

1022
00:39:09,960 --> 00:39:10,793
you don't want to be thinking

1023
00:39:10,793 --> 00:39:11,730
about what's going on in your stomach

1024
00:39:11,730 --> 00:39:12,960
or how quickly you're breathing.

1025
00:39:12,960 --> 00:39:15,600
I'm certainly trying to
ignore all those signals,

1026
00:39:15,600 --> 00:39:17,340
those sensations now.

1027
00:39:17,340 --> 00:39:20,730
But for somebody who has no
awareness of what's going on,

1028
00:39:20,730 --> 00:39:23,040
very little interoceptive awareness,

1029
00:39:23,040 --> 00:39:24,900
that can be problematic, too,

1030
00:39:24,900 --> 00:39:26,550
because these are the very people

1031
00:39:26,550 --> 00:39:28,500
who can ignore the fact that
they're having a heart attack

1032
00:39:28,500 --> 00:39:31,410
or can ignore the fact that
they have high blood pressure

1033
00:39:31,410 --> 00:39:34,230
and are carrying about life
focused on everything external

1034
00:39:34,230 --> 00:39:35,910
with no awareness of their own body.

1035
00:39:35,910 --> 00:39:38,730
They're, quote, unquote, out
of touch with their body.

1036
00:39:38,730 --> 00:39:42,990
So we want to be very careful
about placing valence,

1037
00:39:42,990 --> 00:39:45,270
which is a sort of value of good or bad

1038
00:39:45,270 --> 00:39:48,270
on interoceptive awareness
versus exteroceptive awareness.

1039
00:39:48,270 --> 00:39:49,890
More importantly, we want to emphasize

1040
00:39:49,890 --> 00:39:52,650
that when you undergo
a meditation practice,

1041
00:39:52,650 --> 00:39:54,930
if it's of the sort where
you stop your movement

1042
00:39:54,930 --> 00:39:56,340
and close your eyes,

1043
00:39:56,340 --> 00:39:59,370
you are training for
interoceptive awareness.

1044
00:39:59,370 --> 00:40:02,730
This becomes important later
when we get into discussions

1045
00:40:02,730 --> 00:40:06,060
about meditation for reducing anxiety.

1046
00:40:06,060 --> 00:40:08,430
Some people may opt,

1047
00:40:08,430 --> 00:40:10,740
in fact, I would say
some people ought to opt

1048
00:40:10,740 --> 00:40:11,880
for a meditative practice

1049
00:40:11,880 --> 00:40:14,820
which involves more
exteroceptive awareness,

1050
00:40:14,820 --> 00:40:17,100
actually a meditation
like a walking meditation

1051
00:40:17,100 --> 00:40:18,570
or even a seated meditation

1052
00:40:18,570 --> 00:40:20,040
where they are bringing their focus

1053
00:40:20,040 --> 00:40:22,680
to a place outside their body

1054
00:40:22,680 --> 00:40:24,510
as opposed to inside their body.

1055
00:40:24,510 --> 00:40:26,730
And in fact, there are examples of people

1056
00:40:26,730 --> 00:40:28,410
who have meditated quite a lot

1057
00:40:28,410 --> 00:40:31,140
who develop such a
heightened state or awareness

1058
00:40:31,140 --> 00:40:33,480
of their interoceptive components,

1059
00:40:33,480 --> 00:40:35,430
that is, just fancy, again, nerd speak

1060
00:40:35,430 --> 00:40:38,400
for so aware of their
breathing and of their heart

1061
00:40:38,400 --> 00:40:40,230
and of the state of their gut

1062
00:40:40,230 --> 00:40:43,200
that it actually is intrusive
for daily activities.

1063
00:40:43,200 --> 00:40:47,280
So I will ask you to ask this
question of yourself now.

1064
00:40:47,280 --> 00:40:50,130
Are you somebody who
tends to be very in touch

1065
00:40:50,130 --> 00:40:51,930
with your bodily sensations,

1066
00:40:51,930 --> 00:40:54,420
so, for instance, from the skin inwards?

1067
00:40:54,420 --> 00:40:57,150
Or are you somebody who tends
to be less in touch with

1068
00:40:57,150 --> 00:41:00,360
or aware of your interoceptive state?

1069
00:41:00,360 --> 00:41:01,860
There is no right or wrong answer.

1070
00:41:01,860 --> 00:41:03,870
You don't get an A or an F or a D or a C

1071
00:41:03,870 --> 00:41:04,890
depending on your answer.

1072
00:41:04,890 --> 00:41:06,420
It's just a good question

1073
00:41:06,420 --> 00:41:08,130
for each and every one of us to answer,

1074
00:41:08,130 --> 00:41:11,280
and I think most people
will answer that it depends.

1075
00:41:11,280 --> 00:41:13,680
It depends on whether or not
you are in a social setting

1076
00:41:13,680 --> 00:41:15,090
or whether or not you're alone.

1077
00:41:15,090 --> 00:41:18,240
But we are going to return to
that answer so keep it in mind

1078
00:41:18,240 --> 00:41:20,310
because it will become very beneficial

1079
00:41:20,310 --> 00:41:23,700
in building an optimal
meditation practice for you.

1080
00:41:23,700 --> 00:41:24,780
But for now, just note,

1081
00:41:24,780 --> 00:41:26,601
there's this continuum of perception,

1082
00:41:26,601 --> 00:41:28,230
interoception and exteroception.

1083
00:41:28,230 --> 00:41:30,180
Closing your eyes increases interoception.

1084
00:41:30,180 --> 00:41:33,510
Opening your eyes dramatically
increases exteroception

1085
00:41:33,510 --> 00:41:34,950
just automatically,

1086
00:41:34,950 --> 00:41:36,840
just automatically because
so much of your brain,

1087
00:41:36,840 --> 00:41:39,390
in fact, 40% or more,
is dedicated to vision.

1088
00:41:39,390 --> 00:41:40,980
And this, I should say, for those of you

1089
00:41:40,980 --> 00:41:42,390
that are low vision or no vision

1090
00:41:42,390 --> 00:41:45,030
and those of you that are
blind or have poor vision,

1091
00:41:45,030 --> 00:41:48,780
this entire process is
translated to the auditory,

1092
00:41:48,780 --> 00:41:49,863
to the sound domain,

1093
00:41:50,880 --> 00:41:52,980
so it's true for people that can see

1094
00:41:52,980 --> 00:41:54,900
and it's true for people that can't see.

1095
00:41:54,900 --> 00:41:56,640
Of course, people that
can't see, closing the eyes

1096
00:41:56,640 --> 00:41:59,490
doesn't have this huge
shift towards interoception,

1097
00:41:59,490 --> 00:42:01,560
but there have been a few studies,

1098
00:42:01,560 --> 00:42:03,120
not as many as I would've liked to find,

1099
00:42:03,120 --> 00:42:06,480
but a few studies of, for
instance, people who are blind

1100
00:42:06,480 --> 00:42:08,280
or have low vision, don't see very well,

1101
00:42:08,280 --> 00:42:10,170
and when they close their ears

1102
00:42:10,170 --> 00:42:12,060
and they can't hear the external world

1103
00:42:12,060 --> 00:42:14,490
or they put headphones on or
noise-canceling headphones,

1104
00:42:14,490 --> 00:42:17,940
then the world inside of
them becomes very prominent

1105
00:42:17,940 --> 00:42:20,670
relative to the world outside
of them for obvious reasons.

1106
00:42:20,670 --> 00:42:22,080
So I asked you to ask yourself

1107
00:42:22,080 --> 00:42:23,220
whether or not you are somebody

1108
00:42:23,220 --> 00:42:26,730
who tends to be more
interoceptively aware or not,

1109
00:42:26,730 --> 00:42:29,580
more exteroceptively aware or not.

1110
00:42:29,580 --> 00:42:31,800
And some of you might not be
able to answer that question,

1111
00:42:31,800 --> 00:42:33,990
and if you can't, chances are

1112
00:42:33,990 --> 00:42:36,750
that you are effectively
sliding along that continuum

1113
00:42:36,750 --> 00:42:38,910
depending on the activities
that you're doing.

1114
00:42:38,910 --> 00:42:40,500
So you're probably the kind of person

1115
00:42:40,500 --> 00:42:41,850
where if somebody comes over to you

1116
00:42:41,850 --> 00:42:42,683
and starts talking to you,

1117
00:42:42,683 --> 00:42:44,640
you will engage in that conversation,

1118
00:42:44,640 --> 00:42:47,220
and you don't feel so inside your body

1119
00:42:47,220 --> 00:42:48,960
that you're thinking
about your heart beating

1120
00:42:48,960 --> 00:42:50,610
and whether or not you're
flushing red, et cetera,

1121
00:42:50,610 --> 00:42:52,350
you're going to pay
attention to what they say.

1122
00:42:52,350 --> 00:42:55,620
Many people, however, when
somebody talks to them,

1123
00:42:55,620 --> 00:42:57,300
if they have social anxiety

1124
00:42:57,300 --> 00:42:59,640
or even a slight bit of social anxiety,

1125
00:42:59,640 --> 00:43:01,560
will be thinking about whether or not

1126
00:43:01,560 --> 00:43:02,520
their cheeks are flushing

1127
00:43:02,520 --> 00:43:04,920
or whether or not they
look right or sound right

1128
00:43:04,920 --> 00:43:06,510
or whether or not they have
something in their teeth.

1129
00:43:06,510 --> 00:43:08,310
These are normal responses,

1130
00:43:08,310 --> 00:43:10,290
but they really speak to this issue

1131
00:43:10,290 --> 00:43:11,910
of whether or not you tend to shift

1132
00:43:11,910 --> 00:43:13,530
more towards interoceptive awareness

1133
00:43:13,530 --> 00:43:14,790
or exteroceptive awareness.

1134
00:43:14,790 --> 00:43:16,410
And, of course, it's context dependent.

1135
00:43:16,410 --> 00:43:17,520
It will depend on whether or not

1136
00:43:17,520 --> 00:43:19,200
you're, you know, out
on a date with somebody

1137
00:43:19,200 --> 00:43:21,840
that, you know, you would
loathe to find out later

1138
00:43:21,840 --> 00:43:23,760
that you had food in your teeth

1139
00:43:23,760 --> 00:43:24,810
or whether or not you're with somebody

1140
00:43:24,810 --> 00:43:25,680
you're more familiar with

1141
00:43:25,680 --> 00:43:27,570
where that would not really matter much

1142
00:43:27,570 --> 00:43:29,910
or the other person would
tell you this kind of thing.

1143
00:43:29,910 --> 00:43:33,630
What does it mean to be at one
location or another location

1144
00:43:33,630 --> 00:43:37,080
along this continuum of
interoception or exteroception?

1145
00:43:37,080 --> 00:43:39,330
Well, we know what it
means neurally, right?

1146
00:43:39,330 --> 00:43:42,480
We know that if you are
more interoceptively aware,

1147
00:43:42,480 --> 00:43:45,150
your insula and ACC are active,
but that's not very useful.

1148
00:43:45,150 --> 00:43:48,000
That's not helpful as a
tool. That's just a fact.

1149
00:43:48,000 --> 00:43:50,130
Now, there have actually been studies

1150
00:43:50,130 --> 00:43:52,950
of what a meditation practice can do

1151
00:43:52,950 --> 00:43:56,010
in terms of moving you
along this continuum

1152
00:43:56,010 --> 00:43:57,640
from where you naturally sit

1153
00:43:58,650 --> 00:44:00,510
in order to help you function

1154
00:44:00,510 --> 00:44:03,600
not just during the
meditation but at all times.

1155
00:44:03,600 --> 00:44:05,610
And in order to illustrate this,

1156
00:44:05,610 --> 00:44:06,720
I want to start with a description

1157
00:44:06,720 --> 00:44:09,060
of what is now a classic study.

1158
00:44:09,060 --> 00:44:11,610
It's a very cool study,
it has a very cool name.

1159
00:44:11,610 --> 00:44:13,650
It talks about something very important

1160
00:44:13,650 --> 00:44:15,447
that will come up again and
again in today's conversation,

1161
00:44:15,447 --> 00:44:18,420
and that's something called
the default mode network.

1162
00:44:18,420 --> 00:44:19,440
The default mode network

1163
00:44:19,440 --> 00:44:21,390
is a collection of different brain areas

1164
00:44:21,390 --> 00:44:22,590
that essentially are active

1165
00:44:22,590 --> 00:44:24,570
when we're not doing much of anything

1166
00:44:24,570 --> 00:44:28,200
and certainly is active
when we are not focused

1167
00:44:28,200 --> 00:44:31,710
on one particular task or
conversation or activity.

1168
00:44:31,710 --> 00:44:35,010
The default mode network can
be thought of more or less

1169
00:44:35,010 --> 00:44:38,250
as the network that
generates mind wandering

1170
00:44:38,250 --> 00:44:40,310
or our thoughts drifting from the past

1171
00:44:40,310 --> 00:44:41,790
to the present to the future.

1172
00:44:41,790 --> 00:44:43,050
Remember, earlier, I talked about

1173
00:44:43,050 --> 00:44:44,970
how your perceptual spotlight

1174
00:44:44,970 --> 00:44:47,790
can either be two spotlights
or they can merge.

1175
00:44:47,790 --> 00:44:49,830
Well, similarly, human beings

1176
00:44:49,830 --> 00:44:51,630
can think about the past, surely,

1177
00:44:51,630 --> 00:44:55,200
the present, definitely, and the future.

1178
00:44:55,200 --> 00:44:58,410
And it turns out we can
also split our thoughts

1179
00:44:58,410 --> 00:45:00,450
just like we can split our perception

1180
00:45:00,450 --> 00:45:02,670
into two of those three things,

1181
00:45:02,670 --> 00:45:05,310
so I can think about
the past, a past event,

1182
00:45:05,310 --> 00:45:06,540
and I can think about the present.

1183
00:45:06,540 --> 00:45:09,270
I can split my thinking
and my memory in that way.

1184
00:45:09,270 --> 00:45:11,160
I can also think about the
present and the future.

1185
00:45:11,160 --> 00:45:14,190
I can also think about
the future and the past,

1186
00:45:14,190 --> 00:45:17,730
although it's very difficult,
although not impossible,

1187
00:45:17,730 --> 00:45:19,980
to split one's thinking and memory

1188
00:45:19,980 --> 00:45:22,620
into the past, the present,
and future simultaneously,

1189
00:45:22,620 --> 00:45:23,880
not easily done,

1190
00:45:23,880 --> 00:45:27,360
but pretty easy to split
one's attention and thinking

1191
00:45:27,360 --> 00:45:28,920
into two of those three things,

1192
00:45:28,920 --> 00:45:31,350
either the past, the
present, and the future

1193
00:45:31,350 --> 00:45:34,140
or any two of those three things, okay?

1194
00:45:34,140 --> 00:45:35,910
Just like with attentional spotlighting,

1195
00:45:35,910 --> 00:45:38,790
you can place your mind, your
thinking, and your memory,

1196
00:45:38,790 --> 00:45:41,640
your cognition onto one of those things

1197
00:45:41,640 --> 00:45:43,260
and be very, very present

1198
00:45:43,260 --> 00:45:46,320
or the past and the present
and so on and so forth.

1199
00:45:46,320 --> 00:45:48,540
The default mode network,

1200
00:45:48,540 --> 00:45:50,610
while it involves a lot
of different brain areas,

1201
00:45:50,610 --> 00:45:54,780
can be thought of simply as
the network of brain areas

1202
00:45:54,780 --> 00:45:57,480
that are active when
your mind is wandering

1203
00:45:57,480 --> 00:45:59,220
between these different time domains.

1204
00:45:59,220 --> 00:46:00,780
And the paper I'd like to share with you,

1205
00:46:00,780 --> 00:46:02,580
as I mentioned before,
is now a classic paper,

1206
00:46:02,580 --> 00:46:04,800
it has a wonderful title,

1207
00:46:04,800 --> 00:46:08,220
which is A Wandering
Mind is an Unhappy Mind.

1208
00:46:08,220 --> 00:46:09,960
Now, that sounds almost
like a news article

1209
00:46:09,960 --> 00:46:12,600
or a news article about
a scientific paper,

1210
00:46:12,600 --> 00:46:14,820
but that's actually the
title of the scientific paper

1211
00:46:14,820 --> 00:46:16,950
which was published in
the journal, "Science,"

1212
00:46:16,950 --> 00:46:19,080
which is one of the three apex journals.

1213
00:46:19,080 --> 00:46:21,210
You know, scientific
publishing is competitive,

1214
00:46:21,210 --> 00:46:22,950
but it's especially competitive

1215
00:46:22,950 --> 00:46:26,880
to get manuscripts accepted
into "Science," into "Nature,"

1216
00:46:26,880 --> 00:46:28,050
and into the journal "Cell,"

1217
00:46:28,050 --> 00:46:32,310
so it represents kind of the
Super Bowl, NBA Championships,

1218
00:46:32,310 --> 00:46:34,047
and Stanley Cup, if you will,

1219
00:46:34,047 --> 00:46:36,690
for you sports aficionados
of scientific publishing.

1220
00:46:36,690 --> 00:46:39,600
This is a paper from Matthew
Killingsworth and Dan Gilbert.

1221
00:46:39,600 --> 00:46:41,610
It was published in 2010,

1222
00:46:41,610 --> 00:46:43,110
but it's still considered a classic.

1223
00:46:43,110 --> 00:46:45,720
And this paper, A Wandering
Mind is an Unhappy Mind,

1224
00:46:45,720 --> 00:46:47,160
has a number of very important points.

1225
00:46:47,160 --> 00:46:49,680
I'm going to paraphrase
certain elements of it for you

1226
00:46:49,680 --> 00:46:52,260
because they say essentially
what I would like you to know

1227
00:46:52,260 --> 00:46:54,960
far better than I could say.

1228
00:46:54,960 --> 00:46:57,450
So first of all, they
started out with a statement,

1229
00:46:57,450 --> 00:46:59,730
which I confess I disagree with,

1230
00:46:59,730 --> 00:47:01,560
which is, "Unlike other animals,

1231
00:47:01,560 --> 00:47:03,120
human beings spend a lot of time

1232
00:47:03,120 --> 00:47:05,670
thinking about what is
not going on around them:

1233
00:47:05,670 --> 00:47:07,770
contemplating events that
happened in the past,

1234
00:47:07,770 --> 00:47:10,830
might happen in the future,
or will never happen at all."

1235
00:47:10,830 --> 00:47:13,710
I agree with their assertion
that human beings do that.

1236
00:47:13,710 --> 00:47:15,300
That's certainly my experience,

1237
00:47:15,300 --> 00:47:16,530
although I must say,

1238
00:47:16,530 --> 00:47:18,960
I don't think there's
any evidence whatsoever

1239
00:47:18,960 --> 00:47:21,570
that other animals don't do it also.

1240
00:47:21,570 --> 00:47:23,880
So my apologies,
Killingsworth and Gilbert,

1241
00:47:23,880 --> 00:47:25,620
but I'd be happy to go
toe-to-toe with you on that.

1242
00:47:25,620 --> 00:47:29,190
I am not aware of any data
that prove one way or the other

1243
00:47:29,190 --> 00:47:30,963
what other animals are thinking.

1244
00:47:31,920 --> 00:47:34,020
So let's set aside other animals,

1245
00:47:34,020 --> 00:47:36,480
and let's focus on the human animal.

1246
00:47:36,480 --> 00:47:39,060
Now, their point is still a very good one,

1247
00:47:39,060 --> 00:47:42,450
which is that humans have
this wandering of the mind

1248
00:47:42,450 --> 00:47:44,430
that they call
stimulus-independent thought.

1249
00:47:44,430 --> 00:47:47,250
That is, there's nothing
happening to create these thoughts

1250
00:47:47,250 --> 00:47:49,740
or anything happening in
the immediate environment.

1251
00:47:49,740 --> 00:47:52,440
These thoughts are just happening
on their own internally.

1252
00:47:52,440 --> 00:47:54,900
That's the default mode network.

1253
00:47:54,900 --> 00:47:56,280
This study was important.

1254
00:47:56,280 --> 00:47:57,570
In fact, it was a landmark study

1255
00:47:57,570 --> 00:47:59,310
because they did it right about the time

1256
00:47:59,310 --> 00:48:03,330
that smartphones became
widely available and in use,

1257
00:48:03,330 --> 00:48:04,620
so again, 2010.

1258
00:48:04,620 --> 00:48:06,780
So they basically pinged people,

1259
00:48:06,780 --> 00:48:11,780
they contacted people on their
iPhones many times per day,

1260
00:48:11,910 --> 00:48:16,020
and they did this for
well over 2,200 adults.

1261
00:48:16,020 --> 00:48:19,830
They had a mix of male and
female people in this study.

1262
00:48:19,830 --> 00:48:22,050
The mean age was 34 years,
but there was a range,

1263
00:48:22,050 --> 00:48:23,670
mean, of course, being average,

1264
00:48:23,670 --> 00:48:26,610
but there were a range of
different ages and so forth.

1265
00:48:26,610 --> 00:48:28,147
And at any moment, they asked people,

1266
00:48:28,147 --> 00:48:29,940
"What are you feeling right now?"

1267
00:48:29,940 --> 00:48:32,580
And they also asked them,
"What are you doing right now?"

1268
00:48:32,580 --> 00:48:34,650
So they were looking for
the match or mismatch

1269
00:48:34,650 --> 00:48:36,750
between what people were doing
and what they were feeling.

1270
00:48:36,750 --> 00:48:38,190
They were essentially trying to probe

1271
00:48:38,190 --> 00:48:39,750
what people were thinking about,

1272
00:48:39,750 --> 00:48:41,370
and they also addressed that.

1273
00:48:41,370 --> 00:48:45,600
And they came up with a kind
of a bubble chart, if you will,

1274
00:48:45,600 --> 00:48:47,370
where the bigger the bubble,

1275
00:48:47,370 --> 00:48:50,460
the more answers came back
about one particular thing,

1276
00:48:50,460 --> 00:48:51,810
and they assessed whether or not

1277
00:48:51,810 --> 00:48:54,330
people were happy or not in
that moment, or sad or not,

1278
00:48:54,330 --> 00:48:55,260
whether or not they were focused

1279
00:48:55,260 --> 00:48:56,700
on what they were doing or not.

1280
00:48:56,700 --> 00:48:58,080
There are a lot of bubbles in this chart,

1281
00:48:58,080 --> 00:48:59,460
so I'm not going to read them all.

1282
00:48:59,460 --> 00:49:02,340
But the important points
that came from the data,

1283
00:49:02,340 --> 00:49:04,260
and, again, this is a very large data set,

1284
00:49:04,260 --> 00:49:06,150
was that, and here
again, I'm paraphrasing,

1285
00:49:06,150 --> 00:49:08,220
first, people's minds wandered frequently

1286
00:49:08,220 --> 00:49:10,143
regardless of what they were doing.

1287
00:49:10,980 --> 00:49:14,370
In nearly half of the samples taken,

1288
00:49:14,370 --> 00:49:16,710
people were generally
thinking about something else,

1289
00:49:16,710 --> 00:49:17,940
except, it turns out,

1290
00:49:17,940 --> 00:49:18,930
there's this one little bubble

1291
00:49:18,930 --> 00:49:21,570
sitting way far out on the horizon here,

1292
00:49:21,570 --> 00:49:24,810
people claimed, and I'm
inclined to believe them,

1293
00:49:24,810 --> 00:49:28,200
that they tend to be very
focused on making love

1294
00:49:28,200 --> 00:49:29,880
if they were making love in the moment

1295
00:49:29,880 --> 00:49:31,080
where they were pinged on their iPhone.

1296
00:49:31,080 --> 00:49:33,510
Now, why their iPhone was
there with them at that moment,

1297
00:49:33,510 --> 00:49:34,343
I don't know.

1298
00:49:34,343 --> 00:49:37,410
That wasn't included in this
description of the study.

1299
00:49:37,410 --> 00:49:39,870
But all the other activities,
grooming and self-care,

1300
00:49:39,870 --> 00:49:43,260
listening to the news,
watching television,

1301
00:49:43,260 --> 00:49:46,410
relaxing, working, et cetera, et cetera,

1302
00:49:46,410 --> 00:49:47,730
during all those activities,

1303
00:49:47,730 --> 00:49:49,920
people claimed that their
mind wandered a lot.

1304
00:49:49,920 --> 00:49:52,380
And then they also assessed,
of course, their mood

1305
00:49:52,380 --> 00:49:55,950
and how those people
felt at any given moment

1306
00:49:55,950 --> 00:49:57,180
depending on what they were doing

1307
00:49:57,180 --> 00:50:00,930
and how well their mind and their emotions

1308
00:50:00,930 --> 00:50:02,340
matched what they were doing.

1309
00:50:02,340 --> 00:50:03,993
And what they say here is second,

1310
00:50:05,100 --> 00:50:06,900
they revealed that people were less happy

1311
00:50:06,900 --> 00:50:09,330
when their minds were wandering
than when they were not,

1312
00:50:09,330 --> 00:50:12,480
and this was true during all activities.

1313
00:50:12,480 --> 00:50:16,980
And then third, what people
were thinking at a given moment

1314
00:50:16,980 --> 00:50:20,490
was far better a predictor
of their happiness

1315
00:50:20,490 --> 00:50:21,900
than what they were doing.

1316
00:50:21,900 --> 00:50:22,950
So this is interesting

1317
00:50:22,950 --> 00:50:25,500
and I think matches a lot
of people's experience.

1318
00:50:25,500 --> 00:50:27,480
In fact, I think as you
hear about this study,

1319
00:50:27,480 --> 00:50:29,880
many of you will probably
just say, "Well, duh."

1320
00:50:29,880 --> 00:50:31,393
I mean, if you're working
and you don't like your work

1321
00:50:31,393 --> 00:50:34,230
and you're thinking about
something bad that happened,

1322
00:50:34,230 --> 00:50:37,080
well, then of course you're
not going to be happy.

1323
00:50:37,080 --> 00:50:38,520
But the key point of this study

1324
00:50:38,520 --> 00:50:42,690
is that it did not necessarily
have to be the case

1325
00:50:42,690 --> 00:50:44,940
that people were thinking
about something unpleasant.

1326
00:50:44,940 --> 00:50:47,760
In fact, if people were working

1327
00:50:47,760 --> 00:50:49,500
and they were thinking
about something else

1328
00:50:49,500 --> 00:50:53,730
that was pleasant, that
also made them feel unhappy.

1329
00:50:53,730 --> 00:50:57,330
In other words, the mismatch
between being in an activity

1330
00:50:57,330 --> 00:50:59,520
and having our mind elsewhere

1331
00:50:59,520 --> 00:51:01,530
led people to report themselves

1332
00:51:01,530 --> 00:51:03,690
as feeling more unhappy in that moment.

1333
00:51:03,690 --> 00:51:05,970
And when you total this up,
what you find is that people

1334
00:51:05,970 --> 00:51:08,670
are often not present
to what they are doing,

1335
00:51:08,670 --> 00:51:10,800
and that is a great source of unhappiness,

1336
00:51:10,800 --> 00:51:15,800
even if their thoughts are
those of happy, joyful thoughts.

1337
00:51:16,080 --> 00:51:16,980
So this is interesting

1338
00:51:16,980 --> 00:51:20,610
and I think runs counter to
what most of us have heard

1339
00:51:20,610 --> 00:51:21,443
or have been taught,

1340
00:51:21,443 --> 00:51:23,130
which is, you know, think good thoughts,

1341
00:51:23,130 --> 00:51:24,720
you know, try and suppress bad thoughts,

1342
00:51:24,720 --> 00:51:26,670
have a good internal landscape,

1343
00:51:26,670 --> 00:51:28,260
you know, create a good narrative.

1344
00:51:28,260 --> 00:51:33,210
That is all true, but
equally if not more important

1345
00:51:33,210 --> 00:51:36,120
is to have the ability to be fully engaged

1346
00:51:36,120 --> 00:51:38,040
in what you are doing at a given moment.

1347
00:51:38,040 --> 00:51:41,010
That is the strongest
predictor of being happy.

1348
00:51:41,010 --> 00:51:42,600
And there were several other studies

1349
00:51:42,600 --> 00:51:43,590
that followed up on this,

1350
00:51:43,590 --> 00:51:44,730
but their conclusion that they put

1351
00:51:44,730 --> 00:51:46,410
in the final short paragraph of this paper

1352
00:51:46,410 --> 00:51:48,180
I think really captures it beautifully.

1353
00:51:48,180 --> 00:51:49,537
They say, and here, I'm quoting directly,

1354
00:51:49,537 --> 00:51:52,920
"In conclusion, a human
mind is a wandering mind,

1355
00:51:52,920 --> 00:51:55,650
and a wandering mind is an unhappy mind.

1356
00:51:55,650 --> 00:51:58,230
The ability to think about
what is not happening

1357
00:51:58,230 --> 00:52:00,547
in a moment," I added
the in a moment part,

1358
00:52:00,547 --> 00:52:02,940
"is a cognitive achievement

1359
00:52:02,940 --> 00:52:04,920
that comes at an emotional cost."

1360
00:52:04,920 --> 00:52:07,950
So I know I'm not alone in
believing that this paper,

1361
00:52:07,950 --> 00:52:09,420
A Wandering Mind is an Unhappy Mind,

1362
00:52:09,420 --> 00:52:10,890
and we will provide a link to this paper

1363
00:52:10,890 --> 00:52:12,180
in the show note captions,

1364
00:52:12,180 --> 00:52:14,820
is absolutely key in understanding

1365
00:52:14,820 --> 00:52:17,130
why a meditation practice is so important

1366
00:52:17,130 --> 00:52:19,410
because a meditation practice

1367
00:52:19,410 --> 00:52:21,990
is really about adjusting your place

1368
00:52:21,990 --> 00:52:26,220
along that
interoceptive-exteroceptive continuum

1369
00:52:26,220 --> 00:52:30,660
to what you happen to be
experiencing in that moment.

1370
00:52:30,660 --> 00:52:32,820
And while most people think
of a meditative practice

1371
00:52:32,820 --> 00:52:35,520
as focusing on what's going on internally

1372
00:52:35,520 --> 00:52:37,110
with your eyes closed, third eye center,

1373
00:52:37,110 --> 00:52:38,580
focusing on your breathing, et cetera,

1374
00:52:38,580 --> 00:52:41,480
for any number of minutes or
maybe even an hour or longer,

1375
00:52:42,570 --> 00:52:44,220
there are other forms of meditation

1376
00:52:44,220 --> 00:52:46,500
in which your exteroception dominates

1377
00:52:46,500 --> 00:52:50,400
and which you are actively
focusing on things outside

1378
00:52:50,400 --> 00:52:54,090
or beyond the confines of your
skin and internal landscape,

1379
00:52:54,090 --> 00:52:57,210
and that, too, is meditation.

1380
00:52:57,210 --> 00:53:00,780
And if we are to take the work
of Killingsworth and Gilbert,

1381
00:53:00,780 --> 00:53:03,900
this A Wandering Mind is
an Unhappy Mind, seriously,

1382
00:53:03,900 --> 00:53:05,910
and I know a number of
other laboratories have

1383
00:53:05,910 --> 00:53:08,340
and have supported this
research with their findings

1384
00:53:08,340 --> 00:53:09,870
again and again and again,

1385
00:53:09,870 --> 00:53:12,690
what this means is that meditating

1386
00:53:12,690 --> 00:53:14,670
is not necessarily a practice that we do

1387
00:53:14,670 --> 00:53:17,220
divorced from the rest of life.

1388
00:53:17,220 --> 00:53:19,290
Meditation and mindfulness in particular,

1389
00:53:19,290 --> 00:53:21,970
being present to what we
are doing in a given moment

1390
00:53:22,980 --> 00:53:27,450
is one of the essential keys
to happiness and improved mood

1391
00:53:27,450 --> 00:53:30,360
even if what we are doing is unpleasant.

1392
00:53:30,360 --> 00:53:31,830
So that brings us to a tool,

1393
00:53:31,830 --> 00:53:33,900
and it's a tool that any
and all of us can use

1394
00:53:33,900 --> 00:53:36,900
whether or not you tend to
be interoceptively dominant,

1395
00:53:36,900 --> 00:53:38,640
right, that you tend to pay more attention

1396
00:53:38,640 --> 00:53:42,150
to your bodily sensations,
or exteroceptively dominant.

1397
00:53:42,150 --> 00:53:44,460
And, again, if you don't know
the answer to that question,

1398
00:53:44,460 --> 00:53:46,200
there's a simple test that you can do.

1399
00:53:46,200 --> 00:53:49,410
You can just sit down or
lie down, close your eyes,

1400
00:53:49,410 --> 00:53:53,010
and you can ask yourself or assess

1401
00:53:53,010 --> 00:53:55,890
whether or not your
attention tends to fleet

1402
00:53:55,890 --> 00:53:58,860
to things outside of you, right,

1403
00:53:58,860 --> 00:54:02,160
cars honking or going
by, people in the room,

1404
00:54:02,160 --> 00:54:03,960
or whether or not you
tend to be able to focus

1405
00:54:03,960 --> 00:54:05,190
on your internal landscape

1406
00:54:05,190 --> 00:54:07,740
to the exclusion of exteroception
and attention to things

1407
00:54:07,740 --> 00:54:10,140
outside the confines of your skin easily.

1408
00:54:10,140 --> 00:54:12,810
Now, of course, this will
depend on context and situation,

1409
00:54:12,810 --> 00:54:14,850
even how well rested you are, et cetera,

1410
00:54:14,850 --> 00:54:16,590
but that's exactly the point.

1411
00:54:16,590 --> 00:54:19,230
This is the sort of thing you want to do

1412
00:54:19,230 --> 00:54:22,440
every time you decide to
do a meditation practice.

1413
00:54:22,440 --> 00:54:26,340
In fact, I would suggest that you use this

1414
00:54:26,340 --> 00:54:30,150
to determine what meditation
you do at any given moment.

1415
00:54:30,150 --> 00:54:32,640
So let's say you are somebody
who is a regular meditator

1416
00:54:32,640 --> 00:54:34,650
or let's say you're somebody
who's never meditated

1417
00:54:34,650 --> 00:54:37,260
and you'd like to develop
a meditation practice.

1418
00:54:37,260 --> 00:54:40,380
I suggest that you do a test

1419
00:54:40,380 --> 00:54:42,960
of whether or not you are
more interoceptively dominant

1420
00:54:42,960 --> 00:54:46,380
or exteroceptively
dominant in that moment.

1421
00:54:46,380 --> 00:54:48,510
Again, this is not a personality trait.

1422
00:54:48,510 --> 00:54:51,300
This is a question about where
you happen to be in a moment.

1423
00:54:51,300 --> 00:54:53,760
So let's say you're on a
plane or you're in the car.

1424
00:54:53,760 --> 00:54:54,593
If you're in the car,

1425
00:54:54,593 --> 00:54:55,560
please don't close your
eyes while driving,

1426
00:54:55,560 --> 00:54:59,520
that's sort of obvious, but
do this in a safe way, please.

1427
00:54:59,520 --> 00:55:02,610
But stop, close your eyes,

1428
00:55:02,610 --> 00:55:05,700
and assess whether or not you can access

1429
00:55:05,700 --> 00:55:09,750
and focus your attention
primarily on your internal state

1430
00:55:09,750 --> 00:55:12,210
or whether or not your
attention and perception

1431
00:55:12,210 --> 00:55:15,930
gets pulled to something
external, to exteroception.

1432
00:55:15,930 --> 00:55:17,910
And, again, that will vary

1433
00:55:17,910 --> 00:55:20,040
depending on circumstance and who you are.

1434
00:55:20,040 --> 00:55:22,110
Then I suggest opening your eyes

1435
00:55:22,110 --> 00:55:23,910
and trying to focus your attention

1436
00:55:23,910 --> 00:55:26,070
to something external to you

1437
00:55:26,070 --> 00:55:28,350
and seeing or evaluating the extent

1438
00:55:28,350 --> 00:55:31,260
to which you can divorce your perception

1439
00:55:31,260 --> 00:55:33,150
from sensations that occur

1440
00:55:33,150 --> 00:55:35,700
at the level of your skin or internally.

1441
00:55:35,700 --> 00:55:37,740
Now, I should say that
there's no technology,

1442
00:55:37,740 --> 00:55:41,820
at least not that I'm aware
of, absence of fMRI machine,

1443
00:55:41,820 --> 00:55:43,890
in which case, you are
inside an fMRI machine

1444
00:55:43,890 --> 00:55:44,730
while you do this.

1445
00:55:44,730 --> 00:55:46,470
But unless you are in that experiment,

1446
00:55:46,470 --> 00:55:48,330
and most of us aren't,

1447
00:55:48,330 --> 00:55:51,480
there's no technology that
can tell you, for instance,

1448
00:55:51,480 --> 00:55:53,520
whether or not you are
interoceptively dominant

1449
00:55:53,520 --> 00:55:54,900
or exteroceptively dominant

1450
00:55:54,900 --> 00:55:58,170
and whether or not the
ratio is, you know, 75 to 25

1451
00:55:58,170 --> 00:55:59,910
or what have you at any given moment.

1452
00:55:59,910 --> 00:56:02,040
You have to assess this subjectively.

1453
00:56:02,040 --> 00:56:04,590
However, if you sit down, for instance,

1454
00:56:04,590 --> 00:56:06,630
and you notice that you can
equally split your attention

1455
00:56:06,630 --> 00:56:09,810
between internal sensations
and external sensations

1456
00:56:09,810 --> 00:56:11,010
or whether or not you find yourself

1457
00:56:11,010 --> 00:56:12,510
pulled into external sensations

1458
00:56:12,510 --> 00:56:14,310
when you're trying to focus inward

1459
00:56:14,310 --> 00:56:16,800
or you find yourself pulled inward

1460
00:56:16,800 --> 00:56:18,240
when you're trying to focus outward,

1461
00:56:18,240 --> 00:56:20,220
well, that will dictate
the sort of meditation

1462
00:56:20,220 --> 00:56:23,343
that you perhaps ought to
perform in that moment.

1463
00:56:24,450 --> 00:56:26,460
Let me give an example
of how you would do this.

1464
00:56:26,460 --> 00:56:28,080
You would stop in some way,

1465
00:56:28,080 --> 00:56:30,210
so sit or lie down, close your eyes,

1466
00:56:30,210 --> 00:56:35,130
and evaluate whether or not
you can essentially rule out

1467
00:56:35,130 --> 00:56:38,550
or eliminate attention
to all outside events.

1468
00:56:38,550 --> 00:56:40,560
Most people won't be
able to do that entirely,

1469
00:56:40,560 --> 00:56:41,760
but try and focus your attention,

1470
00:56:41,760 --> 00:56:42,680
for instance, on your breathing

1471
00:56:42,680 --> 00:56:44,100
or the typical third eye center,

1472
00:56:44,100 --> 00:56:46,470
you know, focusing at a spot
right behind your forehead.

1473
00:56:46,470 --> 00:56:48,240
If you feel you can do
that reasonably well

1474
00:56:48,240 --> 00:56:50,640
to the exclusion of what's
happening around you,

1475
00:56:50,640 --> 00:56:53,670
well, then an important question arises.

1476
00:56:53,670 --> 00:56:55,260
Should you meditate in a way

1477
00:56:55,260 --> 00:56:57,720
to enhance that interoceptive awareness?

1478
00:56:57,720 --> 00:57:00,060
Or rather, should you meditate in a way,

1479
00:57:00,060 --> 00:57:01,620
for instance, with your eyes open

1480
00:57:01,620 --> 00:57:03,420
and your attention on a particular portion

1481
00:57:03,420 --> 00:57:04,470
of the landscape you're in

1482
00:57:04,470 --> 00:57:08,910
like a tree or maybe even,
you know, an object or a plant

1483
00:57:08,910 --> 00:57:10,950
or something else in your
immediate environment

1484
00:57:10,950 --> 00:57:12,360
to try and cultivate

1485
00:57:12,360 --> 00:57:14,820
or enhance your exteroceptive awareness?

1486
00:57:14,820 --> 00:57:17,640
That's up to you, but my bias would be one

1487
00:57:17,640 --> 00:57:20,610
in which you work against
your default state.

1488
00:57:20,610 --> 00:57:24,360
Again, the default mode
network is where you land

1489
00:57:24,360 --> 00:57:27,273
on this interoceptive-exteroceptive
continuum.

1490
00:57:27,273 --> 00:57:29,760
It's going to lead to more mind wandering,

1491
00:57:29,760 --> 00:57:31,920
whereas when you encourage

1492
00:57:31,920 --> 00:57:34,200
or we could even say force
yourself a little bit

1493
00:57:34,200 --> 00:57:35,820
to anchor your attention

1494
00:57:35,820 --> 00:57:38,313
to either inside your
body or outside your body,

1495
00:57:39,360 --> 00:57:40,590
and you make that decision

1496
00:57:40,590 --> 00:57:43,833
according to what you
are doing less easily,

1497
00:57:44,730 --> 00:57:48,690
well, then you are actively
training up the neural circuits.

1498
00:57:48,690 --> 00:57:50,700
You are engaging
so-called neuroplasticity,

1499
00:57:50,700 --> 00:57:52,920
the brain's ability to change
in response to experience.

1500
00:57:52,920 --> 00:57:57,150
You are deliberately engaging a shift

1501
00:57:57,150 --> 00:57:58,560
along that continuum.

1502
00:57:58,560 --> 00:58:00,300
To make this crystal
clear, what I mean is this.

1503
00:58:00,300 --> 00:58:01,550
Let me give an example.

1504
00:58:01,550 --> 00:58:05,040
If I were to sit down and I
wanted to do some meditation,

1505
00:58:05,040 --> 00:58:06,630
let's just say three
minutes of meditation.

1506
00:58:06,630 --> 00:58:09,090
There's good evidence that even
three minutes of meditation

1507
00:58:09,090 --> 00:58:10,950
can be beneficial for a variety of things,

1508
00:58:10,950 --> 00:58:15,180
including enhanced focus and
enhanced anxiety management.

1509
00:58:15,180 --> 00:58:16,020
Let's say I sit down

1510
00:58:16,020 --> 00:58:18,690
and I notice that I
can really focus inward

1511
00:58:18,690 --> 00:58:21,150
on what's happening at
the level of my skin

1512
00:58:21,150 --> 00:58:24,990
and my internal organs, and
I can rule out everything.

1513
00:58:24,990 --> 00:58:26,370
Maybe that's 'cause the room is quiet

1514
00:58:26,370 --> 00:58:28,950
or maybe it's just because
my brain is in a state

1515
00:58:28,950 --> 00:58:31,920
that I'm particularly good
at that at that moment

1516
00:58:31,920 --> 00:58:33,930
or maybe it's just a natural ability.

1517
00:58:33,930 --> 00:58:37,020
Well then I would opt for a
three-minute meditation practice

1518
00:58:37,020 --> 00:58:40,050
in which I deliberately exterocept,

1519
00:58:40,050 --> 00:58:41,880
that I build up the circuitry

1520
00:58:41,880 --> 00:58:44,400
to focus on something external to me

1521
00:58:44,400 --> 00:58:47,220
because I want, and I think
most people would like,

1522
00:58:47,220 --> 00:58:50,400
to have an adaptive mechanism within them

1523
00:58:50,400 --> 00:58:52,470
so that they can slide
along that continuum

1524
00:58:52,470 --> 00:58:54,150
and they don't default

1525
00:58:54,150 --> 00:58:57,720
to whatever happens to be
easiest for them in that moment.

1526
00:58:57,720 --> 00:58:59,100
Now, if I were to sit down

1527
00:58:59,100 --> 00:59:01,110
and try and focus on
what's going on internally

1528
00:59:01,110 --> 00:59:02,280
and I kept getting distracted

1529
00:59:02,280 --> 00:59:03,720
by things happening outside of me,

1530
00:59:03,720 --> 00:59:06,270
opening my eyes or feeling like
I need to reach for my phone

1531
00:59:06,270 --> 00:59:08,310
or paying attention to
the sounds in the room,

1532
00:59:08,310 --> 00:59:10,970
well, then I would actively
engage a meditation practice,

1533
00:59:10,970 --> 00:59:14,070
in this case, a three-minute
example but it could be longer,

1534
00:59:14,070 --> 00:59:17,790
where I'm deliberately
trying to focus my perception

1535
00:59:17,790 --> 00:59:20,580
on events at the level of
the confines of my skin

1536
00:59:20,580 --> 00:59:21,810
and internally.

1537
00:59:21,810 --> 00:59:22,643
Why do I say this?

1538
00:59:22,643 --> 00:59:26,700
Well, you know, I love to use
the phrase anytime with kids,

1539
00:59:26,700 --> 00:59:28,320
you know, when they say
"This is really hard

1540
00:59:28,320 --> 00:59:29,340
or something's challenging,"

1541
00:59:29,340 --> 00:59:31,140
or adults will say, "That's really tough."

1542
00:59:31,140 --> 00:59:33,690
Well, as my graduate advisor used to say,

1543
00:59:33,690 --> 00:59:35,100
that means you're learning.

1544
00:59:35,100 --> 00:59:36,270
If something were easy,

1545
00:59:36,270 --> 00:59:39,210
if you can perform any
activity or thought, et cetera,

1546
00:59:39,210 --> 00:59:41,640
well, then there is absolutely zero reason

1547
00:59:41,640 --> 00:59:43,650
for your neural circuits to change.

1548
00:59:43,650 --> 00:59:46,380
It's the friction, it's the
feeling that something is hard

1549
00:59:46,380 --> 00:59:49,560
that turns on the enormous
variety of mechanisms

1550
00:59:49,560 --> 00:59:51,180
at the level of cells, et cetera,

1551
00:59:51,180 --> 00:59:54,150
that allow you to potentially
change your neural circuitry.

1552
00:59:54,150 --> 00:59:56,910
So challenge and discomfort

1553
00:59:56,910 --> 00:59:59,370
is the signal to your brain and body

1554
00:59:59,370 --> 01:00:01,050
that something needs to change,

1555
01:00:01,050 --> 01:00:05,190
so I'm encouraging you to
embark on meditative practices

1556
01:00:05,190 --> 01:00:08,610
that are not your default, okay?

1557
01:00:08,610 --> 01:00:11,340
To essentially go against the grain

1558
01:00:11,340 --> 01:00:15,030
of where your interoceptive
bias or your exteroceptive bias

1559
01:00:15,030 --> 01:00:16,710
happens to be at a given moment.

1560
01:00:16,710 --> 01:00:17,730
And, again, this will change.

1561
01:00:17,730 --> 01:00:20,010
For some of you, this
will change across the day

1562
01:00:20,010 --> 01:00:23,280
where early in the day,
you are very, very good

1563
01:00:23,280 --> 01:00:26,190
at doing an
interoceptive-biased meditation,

1564
01:00:26,190 --> 01:00:28,470
and later in the day, you aren't.

1565
01:00:28,470 --> 01:00:30,600
I actually believe, based on
the data that I've covered,

1566
01:00:30,600 --> 01:00:33,090
and we'll get into a few
more papers about this,

1567
01:00:33,090 --> 01:00:35,610
and my lab is actively
working on this as well,

1568
01:00:35,610 --> 01:00:40,610
that a meditative practice can
be made far more effective,

1569
01:00:40,800 --> 01:00:44,100
that is, it can invoke
more neuroplasticity,

1570
01:00:44,100 --> 01:00:48,060
more shift in brain
states and brain circuitry

1571
01:00:48,060 --> 01:00:51,750
if we do not take the easy path,

1572
01:00:51,750 --> 01:00:54,780
that is, we go against the grain

1573
01:00:54,780 --> 01:00:57,810
of what our brain would
naturally do in a given moment.

1574
01:00:57,810 --> 01:00:59,280
So if you're in a crowded airport

1575
01:00:59,280 --> 01:01:01,650
and you're finding that
everything's very distracting,

1576
01:01:01,650 --> 01:01:04,200
well, then that would be a great time

1577
01:01:04,200 --> 01:01:06,900
to do some interoceptive
focused meditation.

1578
01:01:06,900 --> 01:01:09,223
Whereas if you are really in your head,

1579
01:01:09,223 --> 01:01:10,140
you know, you're looping thoughts

1580
01:01:10,140 --> 01:01:11,220
about the past and present,

1581
01:01:11,220 --> 01:01:13,140
maybe you're even in obsessive thought,

1582
01:01:13,140 --> 01:01:16,440
well, that would be a terrific
time, an ideal time really,

1583
01:01:16,440 --> 01:01:18,690
to do a short meditation

1584
01:01:18,690 --> 01:01:20,880
focused on something external to you.

1585
01:01:20,880 --> 01:01:22,830
In both cases, whether
or not you're focused

1586
01:01:22,830 --> 01:01:26,043
on interoceptive bias
or exteroceptive bias,

1587
01:01:27,030 --> 01:01:30,210
you are going against, or I
should say you're pushing back

1588
01:01:30,210 --> 01:01:32,370
against your default mode network.

1589
01:01:32,370 --> 01:01:35,310
I would argue it's going
to be far more effective,

1590
01:01:35,310 --> 01:01:38,430
that is, you're going to
reduce or shift the activity

1591
01:01:38,430 --> 01:01:40,440
of that default mode network far more

1592
01:01:40,440 --> 01:01:42,870
and in a far more beneficial way

1593
01:01:42,870 --> 01:01:46,200
if you actively try and suppress your bias

1594
01:01:46,200 --> 01:01:48,780
toward being more
interoceptive or exteroceptive.

1595
01:01:48,780 --> 01:01:50,970
Now, I think that's immensely beneficial,

1596
01:01:50,970 --> 01:01:53,370
both for the immediate
changes that you experience,

1597
01:01:53,370 --> 01:01:55,830
what others have called a state change,

1598
01:01:55,830 --> 01:01:57,330
because that's what it is,

1599
01:01:57,330 --> 01:02:00,870
and it also can lead to,
as we referred to earlier,

1600
01:02:00,870 --> 01:02:03,960
more neuroplasticity, more
changes in the brain circuits

1601
01:02:03,960 --> 01:02:06,450
that underlie your default mode network

1602
01:02:06,450 --> 01:02:08,400
and lead to what are called trait changes.

1603
01:02:08,400 --> 01:02:11,130
And I want to be very clear
that I am not the first

1604
01:02:11,130 --> 01:02:13,860
to make this state
versus trait distinction.

1605
01:02:13,860 --> 01:02:15,660
That's a distinction that was raised

1606
01:02:15,660 --> 01:02:17,160
in a really wonderful book.

1607
01:02:17,160 --> 01:02:19,170
In fact, I can't recommend
this book highly enough.

1608
01:02:19,170 --> 01:02:22,230
The book is "Altered Traits:
Science Reveals How Meditation

1609
01:02:22,230 --> 01:02:24,990
Changes Your Mind, Brain, and Body."

1610
01:02:24,990 --> 01:02:28,020
This is a book by Daniel
Goleman and Richard Davidson

1611
01:02:28,020 --> 01:02:30,240
who've done terrific
work and many writings

1612
01:02:30,240 --> 01:02:32,640
and many TED Talks, et
cetera, about meditation.

1613
01:02:32,640 --> 01:02:36,390
I would say that circa 2016, 2017,

1614
01:02:36,390 --> 01:02:38,460
this book really captured

1615
01:02:38,460 --> 01:02:41,250
what I believe to be the
most essential elements

1616
01:02:41,250 --> 01:02:42,480
of the science of meditation

1617
01:02:42,480 --> 01:02:44,640
and a lot of the history of it as well.

1618
01:02:44,640 --> 01:02:45,690
Today, we are focusing

1619
01:02:45,690 --> 01:02:47,250
on much of what's covered in this book

1620
01:02:47,250 --> 01:02:48,083
but also a lot of things

1621
01:02:48,083 --> 01:02:50,850
that have happened, excuse me, since 2017.

1622
01:02:50,850 --> 01:02:52,950
In fact, most of the papers
that I'm going to talk about

1623
01:02:52,950 --> 01:02:55,503
are papers that were published after 2017.

1624
01:02:55,503 --> 01:02:56,940
But, again, this is a wonderful book

1625
01:02:56,940 --> 01:02:59,040
where they very clearly distinguish

1626
01:02:59,040 --> 01:03:01,140
between state changes and trait changes,

1627
01:03:01,140 --> 01:03:03,870
trait changes being the
more long-lasting ones.

1628
01:03:03,870 --> 01:03:07,350
My read of this book and
the literature that follows

1629
01:03:07,350 --> 01:03:11,100
is, again, that when you
sit down to meditate,

1630
01:03:11,100 --> 01:03:13,230
it is going to be most effective

1631
01:03:13,230 --> 01:03:16,770
to do that interoceptive,
exteroceptive bias assessment.

1632
01:03:16,770 --> 01:03:19,170
Ask yourself whether or not
you are more in your head

1633
01:03:19,170 --> 01:03:21,300
or outside your head, if you will,

1634
01:03:21,300 --> 01:03:23,310
and then to do a meditation practice

1635
01:03:23,310 --> 01:03:27,060
that runs counter to
where you happen to be at,

1636
01:03:27,060 --> 01:03:29,340
that is, that pushes you more externally

1637
01:03:29,340 --> 01:03:30,540
if you're in your head,

1638
01:03:30,540 --> 01:03:33,090
and if you're more focused on
what's going on around you,

1639
01:03:33,090 --> 01:03:35,070
that pushes you more internally.

1640
01:03:35,070 --> 01:03:36,480
Now, I think most people are familiar

1641
01:03:36,480 --> 01:03:39,270
with how to do an
interoceptive-biased meditation.

1642
01:03:39,270 --> 01:03:40,620
Again, that would be setting a timer.

1643
01:03:40,620 --> 01:03:41,940
Maybe you don't have even set a timer,

1644
01:03:41,940 --> 01:03:43,350
you just sit or lie down, close your eyes,

1645
01:03:43,350 --> 01:03:46,170
focus on that third eye
center behind your forehead

1646
01:03:46,170 --> 01:03:48,960
or focus on your breathing
or your bodily sensations.

1647
01:03:48,960 --> 01:03:50,580
That's typical and often discussed.

1648
01:03:50,580 --> 01:03:53,640
Exteroceptive based meditations,

1649
01:03:53,640 --> 01:03:56,880
you pick a focal point outside

1650
01:03:56,880 --> 01:03:58,650
or beyond the confines of your skin,

1651
01:03:58,650 --> 01:04:01,050
so that could be, for
instance, a point on the wall

1652
01:04:01,050 --> 01:04:03,480
if you are indoors, it could be a plant,

1653
01:04:03,480 --> 01:04:06,390
it could be a point on
the horizon far away.

1654
01:04:06,390 --> 01:04:09,270
What you will find is
that your visual system

1655
01:04:09,270 --> 01:04:10,320
will fatigue a little bit

1656
01:04:10,320 --> 01:04:12,750
when you concentrate your
visual focus at that location.

1657
01:04:12,750 --> 01:04:15,090
I want to remind you
that it is perfectly okay

1658
01:04:15,090 --> 01:04:17,130
and, in fact, necessary to blink,

1659
01:04:17,130 --> 01:04:18,870
so you should blink,
you can relax your face,

1660
01:04:18,870 --> 01:04:20,010
you can change your expression.

1661
01:04:20,010 --> 01:04:22,650
There is no rule that says
that you can't do those things.

1662
01:04:22,650 --> 01:04:25,710
This is not, you know, just
beaming a particular location

1663
01:04:25,710 --> 01:04:27,630
in space and holding your eyelids open.

1664
01:04:27,630 --> 01:04:30,120
I've been accused many times
of not blinking very often.

1665
01:04:30,120 --> 01:04:31,020
That's for other reasons.

1666
01:04:31,020 --> 01:04:33,180
It's part of the way I access memory

1667
01:04:33,180 --> 01:04:34,200
about what I want to say.

1668
01:04:34,200 --> 01:04:35,490
I don't use a prompter here,

1669
01:04:35,490 --> 01:04:40,230
so I'm accessing from a sort
of internal image in my head.

1670
01:04:40,230 --> 01:04:41,400
That's how my memory works.

1671
01:04:41,400 --> 01:04:42,630
But in any case,

1672
01:04:42,630 --> 01:04:45,840
if you're going to do an
exteroceptive-biased meditation,

1673
01:04:45,840 --> 01:04:47,220
there is absolutely no reason

1674
01:04:47,220 --> 01:04:49,410
why you wouldn't look
away from that location

1675
01:04:49,410 --> 01:04:50,250
every once in a while

1676
01:04:50,250 --> 01:04:51,450
in the same way

1677
01:04:51,450 --> 01:04:53,400
that if you were focused
on internal thoughts

1678
01:04:53,400 --> 01:04:55,470
with your eyes closed and
focused on your breathing,

1679
01:04:55,470 --> 01:04:56,550
every once in a while,

1680
01:04:56,550 --> 01:05:00,570
your thoughts will skip
away from that breathing

1681
01:05:00,570 --> 01:05:01,680
or from your third eye center.

1682
01:05:01,680 --> 01:05:05,190
In fact, and this is discussed
in the book "Altered Traits"

1683
01:05:05,190 --> 01:05:07,590
but by many other people as well,

1684
01:05:07,590 --> 01:05:10,140
one of the key elements of
any meditative practice,

1685
01:05:10,140 --> 01:05:12,300
whether or not it's
interoceptively focused

1686
01:05:12,300 --> 01:05:14,250
or exteroceptively focused,

1687
01:05:14,250 --> 01:05:17,640
is that it's really a refocusing practice.

1688
01:05:17,640 --> 01:05:21,270
The more number of times that
you have to yank yourself back

1689
01:05:21,270 --> 01:05:24,120
into attending or perceiving
one specific thing.

1690
01:05:24,120 --> 01:05:26,160
In other words, the more
times your mind wanders

1691
01:05:26,160 --> 01:05:27,540
and you bring it back,

1692
01:05:27,540 --> 01:05:29,880
actually the more
effective that practice is.

1693
01:05:29,880 --> 01:05:32,130
Again, if you can just
focus on one location

1694
01:05:32,130 --> 01:05:33,120
with laser precision

1695
01:05:33,120 --> 01:05:34,860
and your mind never darts away from that

1696
01:05:34,860 --> 01:05:35,760
and you don't have to bring it back,

1697
01:05:35,760 --> 01:05:37,500
well, then there's no neuroplasticity,

1698
01:05:37,500 --> 01:05:40,140
nothing needs to change
because your nervous system

1699
01:05:40,140 --> 01:05:42,330
will effectively know
it's performing perfectly.

1700
01:05:42,330 --> 01:05:43,857
So if you're somebody who
tries to do meditation

1701
01:05:43,857 --> 01:05:45,600
and you find that your mind just wanders,

1702
01:05:45,600 --> 01:05:47,730
just remember every
time you scruff yourself

1703
01:05:47,730 --> 01:05:48,660
and pull yourself back

1704
01:05:48,660 --> 01:05:50,880
to focusing on some location externally

1705
01:05:50,880 --> 01:05:53,460
or focus back on your breath
or your third eye center,

1706
01:05:53,460 --> 01:05:56,790
each one of those aren't just
opportunities to do better,

1707
01:05:56,790 --> 01:06:00,300
they are essential to
the improvement process.

1708
01:06:00,300 --> 01:06:03,480
Think about them as ascending
a staircase of refocusing.

1709
01:06:03,480 --> 01:06:06,540
Every time you refocus, you're
going up one more level,

1710
01:06:06,540 --> 01:06:08,970
another stair, another
stair, another stair,

1711
01:06:08,970 --> 01:06:11,010
and I think that will move you away

1712
01:06:11,010 --> 01:06:12,960
from the kind of judgmental process

1713
01:06:12,960 --> 01:06:14,910
of thinking, "Ugh, like, I
can't focus on anything."

1714
01:06:14,910 --> 01:06:16,470
Pretty soon, what you'll notice

1715
01:06:16,470 --> 01:06:20,550
is that the refocusing
process will happen so quickly

1716
01:06:20,550 --> 01:06:22,170
that you don't even perceive it.

1717
01:06:22,170 --> 01:06:23,940
And, again, this is
something that's borne out

1718
01:06:23,940 --> 01:06:24,930
in the neuroimaging data.

1719
01:06:24,930 --> 01:06:27,660
A lot of people think that they can focus

1720
01:06:27,660 --> 01:06:28,980
with laser precision,

1721
01:06:28,980 --> 01:06:30,630
but actually, what they
are better at doing

1722
01:06:30,630 --> 01:06:34,080
is refocusing more quickly
and consistently over time.

1723
01:06:34,080 --> 01:06:36,000
There's a classic study about this

1724
01:06:36,000 --> 01:06:38,340
in very experienced meditators
that was done in Japan

1725
01:06:38,340 --> 01:06:39,960
where they had people

1726
01:06:39,960 --> 01:06:42,450
with varying levels of meditation ability,

1727
01:06:42,450 --> 01:06:44,310
so some who had never meditated,

1728
01:06:44,310 --> 01:06:46,080
others who were really expert meditators

1729
01:06:46,080 --> 01:06:48,330
with many hundreds if
not thousands of hours

1730
01:06:48,330 --> 01:06:49,650
of meditation under their belt,

1731
01:06:49,650 --> 01:06:52,890
and they had those
people listen to 20 tones

1732
01:06:52,890 --> 01:06:54,870
repeated over and over, the same tone,

1733
01:06:54,870 --> 01:06:56,910
and they found that the expert meditators

1734
01:06:56,910 --> 01:07:00,180
could really focus, and they
did this by brain imaging,

1735
01:07:00,180 --> 01:07:02,460
they could really focus on all 20 tones,

1736
01:07:02,460 --> 01:07:04,290
whereas most people kind of attenuate

1737
01:07:04,290 --> 01:07:05,790
or what's called habituate to the tone

1738
01:07:05,790 --> 01:07:07,080
so that by the 10th or 11th tone,

1739
01:07:07,080 --> 01:07:09,540
their mind is really
going to something else.

1740
01:07:09,540 --> 01:07:12,450
Now, that's wonderful, but
that really just tells us

1741
01:07:12,450 --> 01:07:14,340
the expert meditators have better focus.

1742
01:07:14,340 --> 01:07:18,030
But it turns out that the more
modern neuroimaging studies

1743
01:07:18,030 --> 01:07:19,620
have shown that they
don't have better focus

1744
01:07:19,620 --> 01:07:22,440
such that they're staying in
a very narrow trench of focus.

1745
01:07:22,440 --> 01:07:24,150
What they're doing is
they're exiting focus

1746
01:07:24,150 --> 01:07:26,310
and going back in more quickly,
more quickly, more quickly

1747
01:07:26,310 --> 01:07:27,510
over and over again.

1748
01:07:27,510 --> 01:07:30,090
So rather than think about
your ability to focus,

1749
01:07:30,090 --> 01:07:32,100
think about your ability to refocus,

1750
01:07:32,100 --> 01:07:34,200
and the more number of
times you have to refocus,

1751
01:07:34,200 --> 01:07:35,760
the better training you're getting.

1752
01:07:35,760 --> 01:07:38,160
So earlier, I mentioned doing
this interoceptive-biased

1753
01:07:38,160 --> 01:07:41,460
or exteroceptive-biased
meditation for three minutes.

1754
01:07:41,460 --> 01:07:42,540
Why did I say three minutes?

1755
01:07:42,540 --> 01:07:44,250
Well, three minutes seems
like a reasonable number

1756
01:07:44,250 --> 01:07:48,240
for most people to do
consistently, you know, once a day.

1757
01:07:48,240 --> 01:07:49,760
And in fact, there are some studies

1758
01:07:49,760 --> 01:07:51,917
of one-minute meditations
and three-minute meditations

1759
01:07:51,917 --> 01:07:53,700
and 10 and 60.

1760
01:07:53,700 --> 01:07:56,790
My laboratory has been studying
a 5-minute-a-day meditation,

1761
01:07:56,790 --> 01:07:58,710
and that clearly has benefits,

1762
01:07:58,710 --> 01:08:02,940
but I think it's also clear
that by three minutes,

1763
01:08:02,940 --> 01:08:05,160
many of the benefits
are starting to arrive.

1764
01:08:05,160 --> 01:08:06,960
And so while I'm not pointing

1765
01:08:06,960 --> 01:08:09,450
at any one particular data point here,

1766
01:08:09,450 --> 01:08:13,020
it's very clear that forcing oneself

1767
01:08:13,020 --> 01:08:17,250
to direct one's perception,
that is, your attention,

1768
01:08:17,250 --> 01:08:20,910
to your internal state or
to something external to you

1769
01:08:20,910 --> 01:08:23,250
is immensely beneficial
if you do it consistently

1770
01:08:23,250 --> 01:08:25,590
and is, again, especially beneficial

1771
01:08:25,590 --> 01:08:27,689
if you're focusing your attention

1772
01:08:27,689 --> 01:08:30,569
on the portion of your experience,

1773
01:08:30,569 --> 01:08:32,459
either internal or external to you,

1774
01:08:32,460 --> 01:08:33,810
that is not the one

1775
01:08:33,810 --> 01:08:36,120
that you would default to in that moment.

1776
01:08:36,120 --> 01:08:38,220
And some people have taken
this to the extreme to say

1777
01:08:38,220 --> 01:08:40,290
that, you know, you can even
just move about your day,

1778
01:08:40,290 --> 01:08:41,279
and then every once in a while,

1779
01:08:41,279 --> 01:08:43,409
just do a one breath meditation.

1780
01:08:43,410 --> 01:08:46,109
To be honest, when I look
at the whole of the data,

1781
01:08:46,109 --> 01:08:49,769
